'''David MacNish''' ({{circa}} 1812 &ndash; 10 April 1863) was a New Zealand interpreter, labourer, bricklayer, farmer and [[Pākehā Māori]]. He was born in [[Trelawny Parish]], [[Jaimaca]] in 1812 or 1813,<ref name="DNZB MacNish">{{DNZB|last=Downs|first=Jeff|id=1m31|title=David MacNish|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref> the son of a Scottish-born estate overseer and a slave woman of mixed British and African ancestry<ref name="DNZB MacNish"/> - so he was also a slave, until [[Manumission|manumitted]] by his father in 1820.<ref name="DNZB MacNish"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=McCracken|first1=T|title=James Harrison McCracken and Susan McNeish|date=1965|publisher=|location=Auckland}}</ref>{{Orphan|date=December 2012}}

He was educated in Scotland and England, and travelled to India and Australia before settling in New Zealand at [[Raglan, New Zealand|Raglin Harbour]] and marrying Te Ani, the daughter of the local paramount chief, Te Moanaroa.<ref name="DNZB MacNish"/> They had seven children, all of whom went by the slightly altered surname, McNeish.<ref name="DNZB MacNish"/>

