ard S. |last3=Levie |isbn=978-0195398144 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Oliver Laughland |title= How The CIA Tortured its Detainees |url= https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2014/dec/09/cia-torture-methods-waterboarding-sleep-deprivation |quote= |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=December 9, 2014|accessdate=2014-12-15 }}</ref> Several detainees endured medically unnecessary<ref name="CIA Report's Most Shocking Passages">{{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/12/09/politics/cia-reports-shocking-passages/ | title=CIA Report's Most Shocking Passages | publisher=CNN | date=December 10, 2014 | accessdate=December 16, 2014 | author=Bradner, Eric}}</ref> "rectal rehydration", "rectal fluid resuscitation", and "rectal feeding".<ref>{{cite news |author=Erin Dooley |title=CIA Torture Report: The Most Stunning Findings |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/cia-torture-report-stunning-findings/story?id=27473273 |quote= |work=[[ABC News]] |date=December 9, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-15 }}</ref><ref name= "legal risk">{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2014/12/john-yoo-if-senate-report-is-true-cia-interrogators-are-at-legal-risk/383790/ |title=John Yoo: If the Torture Report Is True, CIA Officers Are at Legal Risk - The Atlantic |newspaper=Theatlantic.com |date=December 16, 2014  |author=Conor Friedersdorf |accessdate= May 7, 2015}}</ref> In addition to brutalizing detainees, there were threats to their families such as threats to harm children, and threats to sexually abuse or to cut the throat of detainees' mothers.<ref>Threats to family
*{{cite web |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2014/12/cia-torture-report-abuses-rectal-feeding |title="Rectal Feeding," Threats to Children, and More: 16 Awful Abuses From the CIA Torture Report |newspaper=Motherjones.com |date=December 9, 2014  |author1=Nick Baumann |author2=Jenna McLaughlin |author3=Patrick Caldwell |author4=Mariah Blake |accessdate= July 10, 2015}}
*{{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/12/09/politics/top-takeaways-cia-torture-report/ |title=Top takeaways from the CIA torture report - CNNPolitics.com |newspaper=CNN |date=December 9, 2014  |author=Jeremy Diamond |accessdate= July 10, 2015}}</ref> 

The number of detainees subjected to these methods has never been authoritatively established, nor how many died as a result of the interrogation regime, though this number is believed to be at least 100.<ref name="MyUser_Salon.com_June_17_2015c">Deaths under torture the CIA admits
*{{cite news |author1=Greg Miller |author2=Karen de Young |author3=Julie Tate  |last-author-amp=yes |title=Newly released CIA files expose grim details of agency interrogation program |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/newly-released-cia-files-expose-grim-details-of-agency-interrogation-program/2016/06/14/6d04a01e-326a-11e6-95c0-2a6873031302_story.html |quote= |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=June 14, 2016|accessdate=2016-06-16 }}
*{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/2009/06/30/accountability_7/ |title=The suppressed fact: Deaths by U.S. torture - Salon.com |newspaper=Salon.com |date=June 30, 2009  |author=Glenn Greenwald |accessdate= June 17, 2015}}</ref> The CIA admits to waterboarding three people implicated in the [[September 11 attacks]]: [[Abu Zubaydah]], [[Khalid Shaikh Mohammed]], and [[Mohammed al-Qahtani]]. A Senate Intelligence Committee found photos of a waterboard surrounded by buckets of water at the [[Salt Pit|Salt Pit prison]], where the CIA had claimed waterboarding was never used.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Brad Knickerbocker |title=Senate report: Interrogation methods 'far worse' than CIA acknowledged |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/DC-Decoder/2014/0412/Senate-report-Interrogation-methods-far-worse-than-CIA-acknowledged|quote= |work=[[Christian Science Monitor]] |date=April 12, 2014 |accessdate=2014-10-26 }}</ref><ref name = "Brutality and Deceit">{{Cite news |author=Mark Mazzeti |title=Senate Torture Report Faults CIA for Brutality and Deceit |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/10/world/senate-intelligence-committee-cia-torture-report.html |quote= |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 9, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-10 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |author=Mark Mazzeti |author2=Scott Shane |title=C.I.A. Abuse Cases Detailed in Report on Detainees|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/26/us/politics/26intel.html |quote= |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 25, 2009 |accessdate=2014-12-10 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://graphics8.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/politics/20090825-DETAIN/2004CIAIG.pdf |title=Special Review: Counterterrorism Detention and Interrogation Activities (September 2001 - October 2003) |work=[[Central Intelligence Agency Office of Inspector General]] |date=May 7, 2004 |accessdate=July 24, 2018 }}</ref> Former guards and inmates at Guantánamo have said that deaths which the US military called suicides at the time, were in fact homicides under torture.<ref>Deaths under torture by US
*{{Cite news |author=Alexander Naaryan |title=To Live and Die in Gitmo |url=http://www.newsweek.com/2015/01/23/guantanamo-bay-suicides-299432.html |quote= |work=[[Newsweek]] |date=January 15, 2015 |accessdate=March 6, 2016 }}
*{{cite web |url=http://harpers.org/archive/2010/03/the-guantanamo-suicides/ |title=The Guantánamo "Suicides" |newspaper=Harpers.org |date=March 1, 2010  |author=Scott Horton |accessdate= June 16, 2015}}
*{{cite web |url=http://pubrecord.org/torture/292/senate-panels-report-links-detainees-murders-to-bushs-torture-policy/ |title=Senate Panel's Report Links Detainees' Murders to Bush's Torture Policy |newspaper=Pubrecord.org |date= April 30, 2009  |author=Jason Leopold |accessdate= June 16, 2015}}</ref> No murder charges have been brought for these or for acknowledged torture related homicides at Abu Ghraib and at Bagram.<ref>{{cite news|last=Shane|first=Scott|title=No Charges Filed on Harsh Tactics Used by the C.I.A.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/31/us/holder-rules-out-prosecutions-in-cia-interrogations.html?_r=0|accessdate=25 January 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=August 30, 2012}}</ref>

Debates arose over whether "enhanced interrogation" violated U.S. anti-torture statutes or [[international law]]s such as the [[United Nations Convention against Torture|UN Convention against Torture]]. In 2005, the [[2005 CIA interrogation tapes destruction|CIA destroyed videotapes]] depicting prisoners being interrogated under torture; an internal justification was that what they showed was so horrific they would be "devastating to the CIA", and that "the heat from destroying is nothing compared to what it would be if the tapes ever got into public domain."<ref>{{Cite news|last=Spillius |first=Alex |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/8121301/No-charges-in-CIA-tape-destroying-case.html |title=No charges in CIA tape destroying case |publisher=Telegraph |date=2010-11-09 |accessdate=2013-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Taylor |first=Peter |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-17990955 |title=BBC News – 'Vomiting and screaming' in destroyed waterboarding tapes |publisher=BBC Newsnight |date=2012-05-09 |accessdate=2013-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/10/world/10tapes.html |title=No Criminal Charges Sought Over C.I.A. Tapes|authors=Mark Mazzetti and Charlie Savage|date=November 9, 2010|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2010/11/09/charges-case-destroyed-cia-interrogation-tapes-justice-official-says/ |title=No Charges in Case of Destroyed CIA Interrogation Tapes, Justice Official Says |publisher=Fox News |date=2010-11-09 |accessdate=2013-03-31}}</ref> The United Nations [[United Nations Special Rapporteur|special rapporteur on torture]], Juan Mendez, stated that waterboarding is torture—"immoral and illegal", and in 2008, fifty-six House Democrats asked for an independent investigation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/pm/content/2010/s3065204.htm |title=PM – UN special rapporteur says waterboarding is torture |publisher=ABC News |date=2010-11-12 |accessdate=2013-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/11/world/americas/11iht-torture.1.13632127.html |title=Congress presses interrogation issue with administration officials|author=Scott Shane|date=2008-06-11|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Goodenough |first=Patrick |url=http://cnsnews.com/news/article/un-torture-expert-says-us-should-probe-bush-era-torture-claims-intention-prosecute |title=U.N. Torture Expert Says U.S. Should Probe Bush-Era Torture Claims With Intention to Prosecute |publisher=CNS News |accessdate=2013-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Warrick |first=Joby |url=https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2008-06-08/politics/36779438_1_special-counsel-interrogation-policies-justice-department |title=Lawmakers Urge Special Counsel Probe of Harsh Interrogation Tactics |publisher=Washington Post |date=2008-06-08 |accessdate=2013-03-31}}</ref>

American and European officials including former CIA Director [[Leon Panetta]], former CIA officers, a Guantanamo prosecutor, and a military tribunal judge, have called "enhanced interrogation" a euphemism for torture.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42887700/ns/world_news-death_of_bin_laden/t/transcript-interview-cia-director-panetta/ |title=Transcript of interview with CIA director Panetta |work=[[NBC Nightly News]] }}</ref><ref name="mcgreal">{{cite news |last=McGreal |first=Chris |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/apr/05/bush-official-torture-condoleezza-rice |title=Former senior Bush official on torture: 'I think what they did was wrong' |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=April 5, 2012 |accessdate=August 16, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Moore |first=Molly |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/08/AR2007060800985_pf.html |title=Council of Europe Report Gives Details on CIA Prisons |work=[[The Washington Post]] Foreign Service |date=June 9, 2007 |accessdate=August 16, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Shane |first=Scott |authorlink=Scott Shane |last2=Savage |first2=Charlie |authorlink2=Charlie Savage |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/04/us/politics/04torture.html |title=Bin Laden Raid Revives Debate on Value of Torture |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 3, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Montgomery |first=David |title=CIA whistleblower Kiriakou gets posh send-off to prison |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/cia-whistleblower-kiriakou-gets-posh-send-off-to-prison/2013/02/21/b3f0a2b8-7c7c-11e2-a044-676856536b40_story.html |quote= |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=February 22, 2013 |accessdate=2013-02-22 }}</ref> In 2009, both President [[Barack Obama]] and Attorney General [[Eric Holder]] said that certain techniques amount to torture, and repudiated their use.<ref name = "Obama & Holder on torture">{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/28574408/ns/politics-white_house/t/obama-names-intel-picks-vows-no-torture/ |title=Obama names intel picks, vows no torture |work=NBC News |date=January 9, 2009 |accessdate=July 23, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stout |first=David |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/16/us/politics/16holdercnd.html |title=Holder Tells Senators Waterboarding is Torture |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 15, 2009 |accessdate=July 23, 2018 }}</ref> They declined to prosecute CIA, DoD, or Bush administration officials who authorized the program, while leaving open the possibility of convening an investigatory [[Truth and reconciliation commission|"Truth Commission"]] for what President Obama called a "further accounting".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalpunch/2009/04/president-ob-25.html |title=President Obama Discusses Possible Prosecution of Bush Administration Officials |work=[[ABC News]] |date=April 21, 2009 |accessdate=July 23, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423025841/http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalpunch/2009/04/president-ob-25.html |archivedate=April 23, 2009 }}</ref>

In July 2014, the [[European Court of Human Rights]] formally ruled that "enhanced interrogation" is torture, and ordered Poland to pay restitution to men tortured at a CIA [[black site]] there.<ref name="European Court of Human Rights">Court confirms enhanced interrogation in Poland is torture
*{{Cite news |author= AFP |title=European court condemns Poland over secret CIA torture prisons
|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/poland/10989149/European-court-condemns-Poland-over-secret-CIA-torture-prisons.html |quote= |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=24 July 2014 |accessdate=2014-10-26 }} 
*{{cite web |url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21645097-cia-tortured-suspected-terrorists-polish-soil-european-court-human-rights-making |title=Europe and the CIA: Paying for torture |newspaper=The Economist |date= February 25, 2015 |author=Editorial staff |accessdate= March 16, 2015}} 
*{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/19/world/europe/poland-court-cia-prison.html |title=Poland to Pay $262,000 to Inmates Held at Secret C.I.A. Prison |newspaper=The New York Times |date= February 18, 2015 |author=Rick Lyman |accessdate= March 16, 2015}}</ref>  In December 2014, the U.S. Senate made public around 10% of the [[Senate Intelligence Committee report on CIA torture]], a report about the CIA's use of torture during the [[George W. Bush]] administration.

==History of approval by the Bush administration==
Almost immediately after the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 attacks]], Bush administration officials conferring by video link from bunkers decided to treat the attacks as acts of war, rather than merely crimes.<ref name = "Yoo NPR interview">{{cite news |author=Frontline |title=Interview with John Yoo: The Torture Question |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/torture/interviews/yoo.html |quote= |work=[[NPR]] |date=December 15, 2011 |accessdate=2014-12-16 }}</ref>  The question arose: were captured prisoners to be treated as prisoners of war? Officials including Justice Department lawyer [[John Yoo]] recommended classifying them as "detainees" outside the protection of the [[Geneva Conventions]] or any other domestic or military law, and incarcerating them in special prisons instead of the barracks-like "prisoner-of-war camp you saw in [[Hogan's Heroes]] or [[Stalag 17]]."<ref name = "Yoo NPR interview"/> On September 17, 2001, President Bush signed a still-classified directive giving the CIA the power to secretly imprison and interrogate detainees.<ref>{{cite book |author=David J. Rothkopf |title=National Insecurity: American Leadership in an Age of Fear |year=2014 |publisher=Public Affairs |quote= . . . the president  . . .. issued a still classified directive that granted the CIA power to imprison and interrogate prisoners without the burdens of heavy oversight that usually constrained the agency.|page= 313| url= |isbn=978-1-61039-340-9 }}</ref>

In late 2001, the first detainees including men like [[Murat Kurnaz]] and [[Lakhdar Boumediene]], later established to be innocent and arrested on flawed intelligence or sold to the CIA for bounties, were brought to hastily improvised CIA/military bases such as Kandahar, Afghanistan.{{sfn|Kurnaz|2007|p=50}} They were subjected to beatings, electric shocks, exposure to extreme cold, suspension from the ceiling by their arms, and drowning in buckets of water.<ref>{{Cite news |author=CBS News |title=Ex-Terror Detainee says U.S. Tortured Him|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/ex-terror-detainee-says-us-tortured-him/ |work=[[60 Minutes]] |date=March 28, 2008 |accessdate=2014-10-26 }}</ref> An unknown number died as a result.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Glenn Greenwald |title=The Suppressed Facts: Death by  U.S. Torture |url=http://www.salon.com/2009/06/30/accountability_7/ |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date=June 30, 2009 |accessdate=2014-10-26 }}</ref>{{sfn|Kurnaz|2007|p=70}} In late 2001 and early 2002, interrogation under torture at secret sites was still ad hoc, not yet organized as a bureaucratic program, nor sanctioned under Justice Department legal cover.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2009/04/21/the-olc-torture-memos-thoughts-from-a-dissenter/ |title=The OLC "torture memos": thoughts from a dissenter |newspaper=Foreignpolicy.com | quote = The focus on waterboarding misses the main point of the program.  Which is that it was a program. [The program was to]  disorient, abuse, dehumanize, and torment individuals over time.| date=April 21, 2009  |author=Philip Zelikow |accessdate= June 16, 2015}}</ref>

As early as November 2001, the CIA general counsel began considering the legality of torture, writing that "the Israeli example" (using physical force against hundreds of detainees) could serve as "a possible basis for arguing . . . torture was necessary to prevent imminent, significant, physical harm to persons, where there is no other available means to prevent the harm."<ref>{{cite news |author=Joshua Keating|title=What America Learned About torture from Israel and Britain|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_world_/2014/12/15/what_america_learned_about_torture_from_israel_and_britain.html|quote= |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=December 15, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-15 }}</ref>

In April 2002 the CIA had captured its first important prisoner, Abu Zubaydah, who was transferred to a CIA black site and at the suggestion of psychologist [[James Elmer Mitchell|James Mitchell]] the CIA embarked on interrogation methods which included sleep deprivation using bright lights and loud music—still prior to any legal authorization from the US Justice Department.<ref name = "Mitchell">{{cite news |last=Risen |first=James |authorlink=James Risen |last2=Apuzzo |first2=Matt |authorlink2=Matt Apuzzo |title=C.I.A., on Path to Torture, Chose Haste Over Analysis |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/16/us/politics/cia-on-path-to-torture-chose-haste-over-analysis-.html |quote= |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 15, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-16 }}</ref>  Later that April Dr. Mitchell proposed a list of additional tactics, including locking people in cramped boxes, shackling them in painful positions, keeping them awake for a week at a time, covering them with insects, and waterboarding, a practice which the United States had previously characterized in war crimes prosecutions as torture.<ref name = "Mitchell"/><ref>{{cite news |author=Eric Weiner|title=Waterboarding: A Tortured History|url=https://www.npr.org/2007/11/03/15886834/waterboarding-a-tortured-history |quote= |work=[[NPR]] |date=November 3, 2007 |accessdate=2014-12-15 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Glenn Kessler |title=Cheney's Claim that the U.S did not prosecute Japanese soldiers for waterboarding |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/fact-checker/wp/2014/12/16/cheneys-claim-that-the-u-s-did-not-prosecute-japanese-soldiers-for-waterboarding/?hpid=z6 |quote= |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 16, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-16 }}</ref>

[[Jose Rodriguez (intelligence officer)|Jose Rodriguez]], head of the CIA's clandestine service, asked his superiors for authorization for what Rodriguez called an "alternative set of interrogation procedures."<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/hard-measures-ex-cia-head-defends-post-9-11-tactics/ |title=Hard Measures: Ex-CIA head defends post-9/11 tactics |work=[[60 Minutes]] |publisher=CBS |date=April 29, 2012 |accessdate=July 25, 2018 }}</ref> The CIA sought immunity from prosecution, sometimes known as a "get out of jail free card."<ref name = "Pugliese">{{cite book |author=Pugliese, Joseph |title=State Violence and the Execution of Law: Biopolitical Caesurae of Torture, Black Sites, Drones|year=2013|publisher=Routledge |quote= |page = 278 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RcGZ_x96exgC&pg=PA173&lpg=PA173&dq=get+out+of+jail+free+card+for+torture&source=bl&ots=8XH7woOt7R&sig=_i3jbIh_mVBX9ChTTw5xykFVe14&hl=en&sa=X&ei=XgafVO_FH8z8yQTEvoGgAw&ved=0CDQQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=get%20out%20of%20jail%20free%20card%20for%20torture&f=false |isbn=0415529743 }}</ref>

In May 2002, senior Bush administration officials including CIA Director [[George Tenet]], National Security Advisor [[Condoleezza Rice]], Vice President [[Dick Cheney]], Secretary of State [[Colin Powell]], Defense Secretary [[Donald Rumsfeld]], and Attorney General [[John Ashcroft]] met to discuss which techniques the CIA could legally use against Abu Zubaydah.<ref name="MarkMazzetti">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/25/washington/25detain.html |title=Bush Aides Linked to Talks on Interrogations |first=Mark |last=Mazzetti |authorlink=Mark Mazzetti |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=July 25, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="BushAwareInterrogations"/><ref name = "Daily Mail chronology">{{cite news |author=Mail Foreign Service|title=Condoleezza Rice 'was first Bush official to approve torture of terror suspects|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1172884/Condoleezza-Rice-Bush-official-approve-torture-terror-suspects.html |quote= |work=[[The Daily Mail]] |date=April 23, 2009|accessdate=2014-12-15 }}</ref> Condoleezza Rice recalled   "being told that U.S. military personnel were subjected in training to certain physical and psychological interrogation techniques ..."<ref name="MarkMazzetti" /><ref name="White House involvement">{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/TheLaw/LawPolitics/story?id=4583256&page=1 |title=Top Bush Advisors Approved 'Enhanced Interrogation' – Detailed Discussions Were Held About Techniques to Use on al Qaeda Suspects |first=Jan |last=Crawford Greenburg |authorlink=Jan Crawford |first2=Howard L. |last2=Rosenberg |first3=Ariane |last3=de Vogue |work=[[ABC News]] |date=April 9, 2008 |accessdate=August 16, 2018 }}</ref> During the discussions, [[John Ashcroft]] is reported to have  said, "Why are we talking about this in the [[White House]]? History will not judge this kindly."<ref name="BushAwareInterrogations">{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/thelaw/lawpolitics/story?id=4635175&page=1 |first1=Jan |last=Crawford Greenburg |authorlink1=Jan Crawford |first2=Howard L. |last2=Rosenberg |first3=Ariane |last3=De Vogue |title=Bush aware of advisers' interrogation talks |work=[[ABC News]] |date=April 11, 2008 |accessdate=July 25, 2018 }}</ref>

After the Justice Department completed what are now known as the [[Torture Memos]], Condoleezza Rice told the CIA that the techniques were approved in July 2002.<ref name = "Pugliese"/><ref name = "Daily Mail chronology"/><ref name="RiceOkayedWaterboarding">{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/04/22/bush-adviser-rice-gave-ok-waterboard.html |title=As Bush Adviser, Rice Gave OK to Waterboard |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012103725/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/04/22/bush-adviser-rice-gave-ok-waterboard.html |archivedate=October 12, 2017 |deadurl=no |work=[[Fox News]] |date=April 22, 2009 |accessdate=July 25, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="SenateReportRice">{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/04/23/cheney.rice.waterboarding/ |title=Senate report: Rice, Cheney OK'd CIA use of waterboarding |work=[[CNN]] |date=April 23, 2009 |accessdate=July 25, 2018 }}</ref> Dick Cheney said "I signed off on it; so did others."<ref name="SenateReportRice"/><ref name="JasonLeopold">{{cite news |url=http://www.atlanticfreepress.com/news/1/6983--cheney-admits-he-signed-off-on-waterboarding-of-three-guantanamo-prisoners.html |first=Jason |last=Leopold |authorlink=Jason Leopold |title=Cheney Admits He 'Signed Off' on Waterboarding of Three Guantanamo Prisoners |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210221047/http://www.atlanticfreepress.com/news/1/6983--cheney-admits-he-signed-off-on-waterboarding-of-three-guantanamo-prisoners.html |archivedate=December 10, 2015 |work=[[Atlantic Free Press]] |date=December 29, 2008 |accessdate=July 23, 2018 }}</ref> In 2010 Cheney said, "I was and remain a strong proponent of our enhanced interrogation program."<ref>{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/ThisWeek/week-transcript-vice-president-dick-cheney/story?id=9818034 |date=February 14, 2010 |title='This Week' Transcript: Former Vice President Dick Cheney |work=[[This Week (ABC TV series)|This Week]], ABC |accessdate=February 27, 2010 }}</ref> In 2009 Rice said "[w]e never tortured anyone;" she maintained the abuse was "not torture," but was "legal", and "right".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/44/2009/04/30/rice_defends_enhanced_interrog.html |date=April 30, 2009 |title=Rice Defends Enhanced Interrogation |first=Glenn |last=Kessler |authorlink=Glenn Kessler (journalist) }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Annie Lowry|title=Condi Rice Defends enhanced interrogation as 'legal" and "right"|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2009/04/30/condi-rice-defends-enhanced-interrogation-as-legal-and-right/ |quote= |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |date=April 30, 2009|accessdate=2014-12-15 }}</ref>

In addition, in 2002 and 2003, the CIA says they briefed several Democratic congressional leaders on the proposed "enhanced interrogation technique" program.<ref name="WarrickAndEggen">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/12/08/AR2007120801664.html |first=Joby |last=Warrick |authorlink=Joby Warrick |first2=Dan |last2=Eggen |title=Hill Briefed on Waterboarding in 2002 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 9, 2007 |accessdate=July 25, 2018 }}</ref> These congressional leaders included [[Nancy Pelosi]], the future Speaker of the House, and House Intelligence Committee Ranking Democrat [[Jane Harman]].<ref name="WarrickAndEggen"/> The response to the briefings was "quiet acquiescence, if not downright support", according to officials present.<ref name="WarrickAndEggen"/>  Ms. Harman was the only congressional leader to object to the tactics being proposed.<ref name="TopMembersOk">{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2007/12/09/report-top-members-congress-were-ok-with-waterboarding-in-2002.html |title=Report: Top Members of Congress Were OK With Waterboarding in 2002 |work=[[Fox News]] |date=December 9, 2007 |accessdate=July 24, 2018 }}</ref> Former senator Bob Graham (D-Fla.), chairman of the Senate intelligence committee after the 9/11 attacks, said he was not briefed on waterboarding and that in three instances agency officials said he'd attended briefings on days that his personal journal shows he was elsewhere.<ref name="Panettabrief">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/05/15/AR2009051502743.html |title=CIA Chief Panetta Rebuts Pelosi's Charges on Interrogation Briefings |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=May 15, 2009 |author=Perry Bacon Jr. |first2=Joby |last2=Warrick |authorlink2=Joby Warrick |accessdate=July 26, 2018 }}</ref>

At least one Bush administration official opposed torturing prisoners, Condoleezza Rice's most senior adviser [[Philip Zelikow]].<ref name="PhilipZelikow">{{cite news |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/30369127/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026033059/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/30369127/ |archivedate=October 26, 2012 |title=Rachel Maddow Interview of Philip Zelikow, Transcript |work=[[MSNBC]] |date=April 23, 2009 |accessdate=July 25, 2018 }}</ref> Upon learning details of the program, Zelikow wrote a memo to Rice contesting the Justice Department's Torture Memos, believing them wrong both legally and as a matter of policy.<ref name="PhilipZelikow"/> Zelikow's memo warned that the interrogation techniques breached US law, and could lead to prosecutions for war crimes.<ref name="mcgreal" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Horton |first=Scott |authorlink=Scott Horton (attorney) |url=http://harpers.org/archive/2012/04/hbc-90008548 |title=Witness for the Prosecution |work=[[Harper's Magazine]] |date=April 5, 2012 |accessdate=August 16, 2018 }}</ref> The Bush Administration attempted to collect all the copies of Zelikow's memo and destroy them.<ref name="PhilipZelikow"/><ref name="SoufanNewsweek">{{cite news |url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/195089 |first=Michael |last=Isikoff |authorlink=Michael Isikoff |title="We Could Have Done This the Right Way" |work=[[Newsweek]] |date=April 25, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090429005436/http://www.newsweek.com/id/195089 |archivedate=April 29, 2009 |deadurl=no |accessdate=July 25, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Dan Michael Smith|title=The memo Bush tried to destroy|url=http://www.salon.com/2012/04/04/the_memo_bush_tried_to_destroy/ |quote= |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date=April 4, 2012|accessdate=2014-12-15 }}</ref> [[Jane Mayer]], author of ''[[The Dark Side (book)|The Dark Side]]'',<ref name="TheDarkSide" /> quotes Zelikow as predicting that "America's descent into torture will in time be viewed like the Japanese internments", in that "(f)ear and anxiety were exploited by zealots and fools."<ref>{{cite news |last=Horton |first=Scott |url=https://harpers.org/blog/2008/07/six-questions-for-jane-mayer-author-of-_the-dark-side_/ |title=Six Questions for Jane Mayer, Author of ''The Dark Side'' |work=[[Harper's Magazine]] |date=14 July 2008 |accessdate=July 25, 2018 }}</ref>

==Development of techniques and training==
[[File:West Coast U.S. Navy SERE insignia.png|thumb|right|200px|West coast, Navy SERE Insignia]]
The authorized "enhanced interrogation" (the originator of this term is unknown, but it appears to be a [[calque]] of the German "{{lang|de|verschärfte Vernehmung}}", meaning "intensified interrogation", used in 1937 by [[Gestapo]] chief [[Heinrich Müller (Gestapo)|Heinrich Müller]]<ref name = "Verschärfte Vernehmung" />) was based on work done by [[James Elmer Mitchell]] and [[Bruce Jessen]] in the Air Force's [[Survival, Evasion, Resistance and Escape|Survival Evasion Resistance Escape]] (SERE) program.<ref name="BrianRoss">{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/images/Blotter/brianross_kiriakou_transcript1_blotter071210.pdf |first=Brian |last=Ross |title=CIA - Abu Zubaydah: Interview with John Kiriakou |work=[[ABC News]] |date=December 10, 2007 |accessdate=July 25, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="TheDarkSide">{{cite book |authorlink=Jane Mayer |last=Mayer |first=Jane |title=[[The Dark Side (book)|The Dark Side: The Inside Story of How the War on Terror Turned Into a War on American Ideals]] |date=2008 |p=199 |isbn=978-0307456298 |publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] }}</ref><ref name="CIA1000Specialists">{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Blotter/story?id=7471217&page=1 |first=Brian |last=Ross |first2=Matthew |last2=Cole |first3=Joseph |last3=Rhee |title=The CIA's $1000 a Day Specialists on Waterboarding, Interrogations |work=[[ABC News]] |date=April 30, 2009 |accessdate=July 25, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="PsychologistsResponsible">{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/04/30/report-psychologists-responsible-devising-cia-torture-program/ |title=Report: Two Psychologists Responsible for Devising CIA Torture Program |work=[[Fox News]] |date=April 30, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503115636/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/04/30/report-psychologists-responsible-devising-cia-torture-program/ |archivedate=May 3, 2009 |accessdate=July 25, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="KatherineEban">{{cite news |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2007/07/torture200707 |title=Rorschach and Awe |first=Katherine |last=Eban |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=July 17, 2007 |accessdate=July 25, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="WarrickAndFinn">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/04/21/AR2009042104055.html |first=Joby |last=Warrick |authorlink=Joby Warrick |first2=Peter |last2=Finn |title=Harsh Tactics Readied Before Their Approval |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=April 22, 2009 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref> The CIA contracted with the two psychologists to develop alternative, harsh interrogation techniques.<ref name="BrianRoss"/><ref name="TheDarkSide"/><ref name="CIA1000Specialists"/><ref name="PsychologistsResponsible"/><ref name="KatherineEban"/> However, neither of the two psychologists had any experience in conducting interrogations.<ref name="CIA1000Specialists"/><ref name="PsychologistsResponsible"/><ref name="KatherineEban"/><ref name="EbanTortureMemos">{{cite news |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/04/torture-memos-link-lawyers-and-psychologists |first=Katherine |last=Eban |title=Torture Memos Link Lawyers and Psychologists |work=Vanity Fair |date=April 17, 2009 |accessdate=July 26, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307093311/https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/04/torture-memos-link-lawyers-and-psychologists |archivedate=March 7, 2016 |deadurl=no }}</ref> Air Force Reserve Colonel Steve Kleinman stated that the CIA "chose two clinical psychologists who had no intelligence background whatsoever, who had never conducted an interrogation... to do something that had never been proven in the real world."<ref name="PsychologistsResponsible"/><ref name="KatherineEban"/><ref name="EbanTortureMemos"/> Associates of Mitchell and Jessen were skeptical of their methods and believed they did not possess any data about the impact of SERE training on the human psyche.<ref name="KatherineEban"/> The CIA came to learn that Mitchell and Jessen's expertise in waterboarding was probably "misrepresented" and thus, there was no reason to believe it was medically safe or effective.<ref name="CIA1000Specialists"/> Despite these shortcomings of experience and know-how, the two psychologists boasted of being paid $1000 a day ({{Inflation|US|1000|2002|r=-1|fmt=eq}}) plus expenses, tax-free by the CIA for their work.<ref name="CIA1000Specialists"/><ref name="PsychologistsResponsible"/><ref name="KatherineEban"/>

The SERE program, which Mitchell and Jessen would reverse engineer, was used to train pilots and other soldiers on how to resist [[Mind control|"brainwashing"]] techniques assumed to have been employed by the Chinese to extract false confessions from captured Americans during the Korean War.<ref name="TheDarkSide"/><ref name="KatherineEban"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/02/us/02detain.html |title=China Inspired Interrogations at Guantánamo|last1=Shane |first1=Scott |date=July 2, 2008 |work=The New York Times|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref> The program subjected trainees to "waterboarding . . . sleep deprivation, isolation, exposure to extreme temperatures, enclosure in tiny spaces, bombardment with agonizing sounds at extremely damaging decibel levels, and religious and sexual humiliation."<ref name="CIAGhostDetainees">{{cite web |url=https://www.hrw.org/legacy/backgrounder/usa/us1004/index.htm |title=The United States' "Disappeared": The CIA's Long-Term "Ghost Detainees" |work=[[Human Rights Watch]] |date=October 2004 |accessdate=July 25, 2018}}</ref> Under CIA supervision, Miller and Jessen adapted SERE into an offensive program designed to train CIA agents on how to use the harsh interrogation techniques to gather information from terrorist detainees.<ref name="BrianRoss"/><ref name="TheDarkSide"/><ref name="KatherineEban"/> In fact, all of the tactics listed above would later be reported in the International Committee of the Red Cross Report on Fourteen High Value Detainees in CIA Custody as having been used on Abu Zubaydah.<ref name="ICRC">{{cite web |url=http://www.nybooks.com/media/doc/2010/04/22/icrc-report.pdf |title=ICRC Report on the Treatment of Fourteen "High Value Detainees" in CIA Custody |work=[[International Committee of the Red Cross]] |date=February 2007 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="DerekSummerfield">{{cite journal |last=Summerfield |first1=Derek |date=April 12, 2003 |title=Fighting 'terrorism' with torture: torture is a form of terrorism: there are no justifications for it |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/25454150 |journal=[[The BMJ]] |volume=326 |issue=7393 |pages=773–774 |doi=10.1136/bmj.326.7393.773 |access-date= }}</ref>

[[Stephen Soldz]], Steven Reisner and Brad Olson wrote an article describing how the techniques used mimic what was taught in the [[Survival, Evasion, Resistance and Escape|SERE]]-program: "the military's Survival, Evasion, Resistance, and Escape program that trains [[US Special Operations Forces]], aviators and others at high risk of capture on the battlefield to evade capture and to resist 'breaking' under torture, particularly through giving false confessions or collaborating with their captors".<ref name="SERE"/>

The psychologists relied heavily on experiments done by American psychologist [[Martin Seligman]] in the 1970s on [[learned helplessness]].<ref name="AmyGoodman">{{cite news |url=https://www.democracynow.org/2008/7/18/the_dark_side_jane_mayer_on |title=The Dark Side: Jane Mayer on the Inside Story of How the War on Terror Turned Into a War on American Ideals |author=Amy Goodman |work=[[Democracy Now]] |date=July 18, 2008 }}</ref> In these experiments caged dogs were exposed to severe electric shocks in a random way in order to completely break their will to resist.<ref name="AmyGoodman"/> Mitchell and Jessen applied this idea to the [[interrogation of Abu Zubaydah]].<ref name="TheDarkSide"/><ref name="AmyGoodman"/> Many of the interrogation techniques used in the SERE program, including waterboarding, cold cell, long-time standing, and sleep deprivation were previously considered illegal under U.S. and international law and treaties at the time of Abu Zubaydah's capture.<ref name="EnforcedDisappearance">{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200708/cmselect/cmfaff/147/147we47.htm |title=Enforced Disappearance, Illegal Interstate Transfer, and Other Human Rights Abuses Involving the UK Overseas Territories: Executive Summary |work=[[Reprieve (organisation)|Reprieve]] |via=publications.parliament.uk |date=October 18, 2007 }}</ref><ref name="WalterPincusWaterboarding">{{cite news |first=Walter |last=Pincus |authorlink=Walter Pincus |date=5 October 2006 |title=Waterboarding Historically Controversial |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/04/AR2006100402005.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=20 April 2009 |page=A17}}</ref> In fact, the United States had prosecuted Japanese military officials after World War II and American soldiers after the Vietnam War for waterboarding and as recently as 1983.<ref name="WalterPincusWaterboarding"/> Since 1930, the United States had defined sleep deprivation as an illegal form of torture.<ref name="TheDarkSide"/> Many other techniques developed by the CIA constitute inhuman and degrading treatment and torture under the United Nations Convention against Torture and Article 3 of the European Convention on Human Rights.<ref name="EnforcedDisappearance"/>

According to [[Human Rights First]]:

<blockquote>Internal FBI memos and press reports have pointed to SERE training as the basis for some of the harshest techniques authorised for use on detainees by [[the Pentagon]] in 2002 and 2003.<ref name="HRF SERE">{{ cite web |url=http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/us_law/etn/dic/mowhoush.asp |title=Command's Responsibility: Detainee Deaths in U.S. Custody in Iraq and Afghanistan |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060815124943/http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/us_law/etn/dic/mowhoush.asp |archivedate=August 15, 2006 |author= |work=[[Human Rights First]] |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref></blockquote>

And ''[[Salon.com|Salon]]'' stated:

<blockquote>A March 22, 2005, sworn statement by the former chief of the Interrogation Control Element at Guantánamo said instructors from SERE also taught their methods to interrogators of the prisoners in [[Cuba]].<ref name="SERE Salon">{{cite news |url=http://www.salon.com/news/feature/2006/06/29/torture/index.html |title=Torture teachers – An Army document proves that Guantánamo interrogators were taught by instructors from a military school that trains U.S. soldiers how to resist torture |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521120758/http://www.salon.com/news/feature/2006/06/29/torture/index.html |archivedate=May 21, 2008 |first=Mark |last=Benjamin |work=[[Salon.com]] |date=June 29, 2006 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref></blockquote>

While [[Jane Mayer]] reported for ''[[The New Yorker]]'':

<blockquote>According to the SERE affiliate and two other sources familiar with the program, after September 11 several [[psychologist]]s versed in SERE techniques began advising interrogators at Guantánamo Bay and elsewhere. Some of these psychologists essentially "tried to [[reverse-engineer]]" the SERE program, as the affiliate put it. "They took good knowledge and used it in a bad way", another of the sources said. Interrogators and [[BSCT]] members at Guantánamo adopted coercive techniques similar to those employed in the SERE program.<ref name="Mayer SERE">{{cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2005/07/11/the-experiment-3 |title=The Experiment – The military trains people to withstand interrogation. Are those methods being misused at Guantánamo? |first=Jane |last=Mayer |authorlink=Jane Mayer |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=July 11, 2005 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref></blockquote>

and continues to report:

<blockquote>many of the interrogation methods used in SERE training seem to have been applied at Guantánamo."<ref name="SERE">{{cite web |url=http://www.counterpunch.org/soldz06072007.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070611011902/http://www.counterpunch.org/soldz06072007.html |archivedate=June 11, 2007 |title=The Pentagon's IG Report Contradicts What the APA Has Said About the Involvement of Psychologists in Abusive Interrogations – A Q&A on Psychologists and Torture |first=Stephen |last=Soldz |first2=Steven |last2=Reisner |first3=Brad |last3=Olson |work=[[CounterPunch]] |date=June 7, 2007 |accessdate=July 25, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="Paul Rester"/><ref name="Mayer">{{cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2007/02/19/whatever-it-takes |title=Whatever it takes: The politics of the man behind "24" |authorlink=Jane Mayer |first=Jane |last=Mayer |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=February 12, 2007 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="washingtonpost.com">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/15/AR2007011501204.html |title=Interrogation Research Is Lacking, Report Says: Few Studies Have Examined U.S. Methods |authorlink=Josh White (journalist) |first=Josh |last=White |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=January 16, 2007 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref></blockquote>

A bipartisan report released in 2008 stated that:

<blockquote>a February 2002 memorandum signed by President [[George W. Bush]], stating that the [[Third Geneva Convention]] guaranteeing humane treatment to [[Prisoner of war|prisoners of war]] did not apply to [[al-Qaeda]] or [[Taliban]] detainees, and a December 2002 memo signed by former [[United States Secretary of Defense|Defense Secretary]] [[Donald Rumsfeld]], approving the use of "aggressive techniques" against detainees held at [[Guantanamo Bay Detention Camp|Guantanamo Bay]], as key factors that lead to the extensive abuses.<ref name="bipartisan-report-2008">{{cite web |url=http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/paperchase/2008/12/us-detainee-abuses-approved-by-senior.php |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216032248/http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/paperchase/2008/12/us-detainee-abuses-approved-by-senior.php |archivedate=December 16, 2008 |title=US detainee abuses approved by senior officials: Senate report |first=Devin |last=Montgomery |work=[[JURIST]] |date=December 12, 2008 }}</ref></blockquote>

However, the Bush administration's February 2002 memorandum had, in fact, stated that only al-Qaeda detainees were not covered by the Geneva Conventions. That same order held that Taliban detainees would be entitled to treatment under [[Geneva Conventions#Common Article 3 relating to Non-International Armed Conflict|Common Article 3 of the Geneva Conventions]].
<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2002/US/02/07/ret.bush.detainees/ |title=Bush: Geneva treaty applies to Taliban detainees |work=[[CNN]] |date=February 7, 2002 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2002/02/20020207-13.html |title=Fact Sheet: Status of Detainees at Guantanamo |work=[[whitehouse.gov]] |date=February 7, 2002 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref> These standards were ordered for all detainees in 2006, al-Qaeda members included, following the Supreme Court's ruling in [[Hamdan v. Rumsfeld]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/5169600.stm |title=US detainees to get Geneva rights |work=[[BBC News]] |date=July 11, 2006 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref>

Donald Rumsfeld rescinded his December 2002 memo after six weeks.<ref name="GitmoMyth"/>

Common Article 3 remains the policy under the [[Obama administration]], and not the balance of the Third Geneva Convention.<ref name=bellinger>{{cite news |last=Bellinger III |first=John B. |authorlink=John B. Bellinger III |url=http://shadow.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2010/08/11/obama_bush_and_the_geneva_conventions |title=Obama, Bush, and the Geneva Conventions |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |date=August 11, 2010 }}</ref>

===Central Intelligence Agency===
[[File:US Senate Report on CIA Detention Interrogation Program.pdf|thumb|The US Senate Report on CIA Detention Interrogation Program that details the use of torture during CIA detention and interrogation.]]

A Congressional bipartisan report in December 2008<ref name="bipartisan-report-2008"/> established that:

<blockquote>harsh interrogation techniques used by the CIA and the U.S. military were directly adapted from the training techniques used to prepare special forces personnel to resist interrogation by enemies that torture and abuse prisoners. The techniques included [[Nudity#Imposed nudity|forced nudity]], painful stress positions, sleep deprivation, and until 2003, waterboarding, a form of simulated drowning.</blockquote>

[[File:WaterboardWithCanKhmerRouge.jpg|thumb|300px|Waterboard on display at the [[Tuol Sleng Genocide Museum]]: prisoners' feet were shackled to the bar on the right, wrists restrained by shackles on the left. Water was poured over the face using the [[watering can]]]] According to [[ABC News]],<ref name="abcnews.go.com">{{Cite journal| url=http://abcnews.go.com/WNT/Investigation/story?id=1322866| title=CIA's Harsh Interrogation Techniques Described| journal=ABC News| date=November 18, 2005}}</ref> former and current CIA officials have come forward to reveal details of interrogation techniques authorized in the CIA. These include:

#[[Waterboarding]]: The prisoner is bound to a [[Trendelenburg position|declined board]], feet raised and head slightly below the feet. Material is wrapped over the prisoner's face and water is poured over them, [[asphyxiating]] the prisoner.
#[[Hypothermia#Water|Hypothermia]]: The prisoner is left to stand naked in a cell kept near {{convert|50|F}}, while being regularly doused with cold water in order to increase the rate at which heat is lost from the body.
#[[Stress positions]]: Prisoners are forced to stand, handcuffed and with their feet shackled to an eye bolt in the floor (and/or wall), for more than 40 hours, causing the prisoners' weight to be placed on just one or two muscles. This creates an intense amount of pressure on the legs, leading first to pain and then muscle failure.
#Abdomen strikes: A hard, open-handed slap is dealt to the prisoner's [[abdomen]]. Doctors consulted over the matter advised against using a punch, which could cause lasting internal damage.
#[[Slapping (strike)|Insult slap]]: An open-handed slap is delivered to the prisoner's face, aimed at causing pain and triggering fear.
#Shaking: The interrogator forcefully grabs the front of the prisoner's shirt and shakes them.
In December 2007, CIA director [[Michael Hayden (general)|Michael Hayden]] stated that "of about 100 prisoners held to date in the CIA program, the enhanced techniques were used on about 30, and waterboarding used on just three.".<ref name="Hayden">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/07/washington/07interrogate.html |title=Lawmakers Back Limits on Interrogation Tactics |first=Scott |last=Shane |authorlink=Scott Shane |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 7, 2007 |accessdate=July 29, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="Hayden on videotapes">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/01/18/AR2008011803347.html |title=Lawyers for Detainee Refer In Filing to More CIA Tapes |first=Carol D. |last=Leonnig |authorlink=Carol D. Leonnig |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=January 19, 2008 |accessdate=July 29, 2018 }}</ref>

The report, "Experiments in Torture: Human Subject Research and Evidence of Experimentation in the 'Enhanced' Interrogation Program", published by the advocacy group [[Physicians for Human Rights]], described personnel in the CIA's Office of Medical Services (OMS) performing research on the prisoners as the above techniques were used both serially and in combination.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Wadman|first=Meredith|title=Medics performed 'interrogation research'|url=http://www.nature.com/news/2010/100607/full/news.2010.284.html |work=Nature.com |accessdate=7 June 2011}}</ref> This report was based on previously [[classified information|classified]] documents made available by the Obama administration in 2010.

According to ABC news in 2007, the CIA removed waterboarding from its list of acceptable interrogation techniques in 2006. ABC stated further that the last use of waterboarding was in 2003.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/theblotter/2007/11/exclusive-only-.html |title=Exclusive: Only Three Have Been Waterboarded by CIA |work=[[ABC News]] |date=November 2, 2007 |accessdate=July 29, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071103132635/http://blogs.abcnews.com/theblotter/2007/11/exclusive-only-.html |archivedate=November 3, 2007 }}</ref>

===Defense Intelligence Agency===
{{Main|Defense Intelligence Agency}}

In 2003, the Defense Secretary [[Donald Rumsfeld]]'s "Working Group" on interrogations requested that the DIA come up with prisoner interrogation techniques for the group's consideration. According to the 2008 [[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services|U.S. Senate Armed Services Committee]] report on the treatment of detainees in U.S. custody, the DIA began drawing up the list of techniques with the help of its civilian employee, a former Guantanamo Interrogation Control Element (ICE) Chief David Becker. Becker claimed that the Working Group members were particularly interested in aggressive methods and that he "was encouraged to talk about techniques that inflict pain."<ref name="scasreport">{{cite report |work=[[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services]] |url=http://www.armed-services.senate.gov/Publications/Detainee%20Report%20Final_April%2022%202009.pdf |format=PDF |title=Inquiry into the Treatment of Detainees in U.S. Custody |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021194943/http://www.armed-services.senate.gov/Publications/Detainee%20Report%20Final_April%2022%202009.pdf |archivedate=October 21, 2013 |date=November 20, 2008 |accessdate=July 30, 2018 }}</ref>{{rp|111}}

[[File:FBI correspondence regarding DIA personnel in Guantanamo.pdf|thumb|right|150px|A declassified FBI correspondence alleging DIA use of [[gay porn]] and humiliating techniques in interrogations]]

It is unknown to what extent the agency's recommendations were used or for how long, but according to the same Senate report, the list drawn up by DIA included the use "drugs such as sodium pentothal and demerol", humiliating treatment using female interrogators and sleep deprivation. Becker claimed that he recommended the use of drugs due to rumors that another intelligence agency, name of which was redacted in the Senate report, had successfully used them in the past.<ref name="scasreport" />{{rp|112}} According to the analysis of the [[Office of the Inspector General, U.S. Department of Defense|Office of Defense Inspector General]], the DIA's cited justification for the use of drugs was to "[relax] detainee to cooperative state" and that mind-altering substances were not used.<ref>{{cite report |work=[[Office of the Inspector General, U.S. Department of Defense|Deputy Inspector General for Intelligence]] |url=http://www.dodig.mil/FOIA/ERR/09-INTEL-13_Redacted.pdf |title=Investigation of Allegations of the Use of Mind-Altering Drugs to Facilitate Interrogations of Detainees |date=September 23, 2009 |page=10 |archivedate=February 22, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222051033/http://www.dodig.mil/FOIA/ERR/09-INTEL-13_Redacted.pdf }}</ref>

Some more lurid revelations of DIA's alleged harsh interrogations came from [[FBI]] officers, who conducted their own screenings of detainees in [[Guantanamo]] along with other agencies. According to one account, the interrogators of what was then DIA's Defense HUMINT Service (currently the [[Defense Clandestine Service]]), forced subjects to watch [[gay porn]], draped them with the [[Flag of Israel|Israeli Flag]] and interrogated them in rooms lit by [[strobe light]]s for 16–18 hours, all the while telling prisoners that they were from the FBI.<ref name="aclu.org">{{cite web |work=[[American Civil Liberties Union]] |url=https://www.aclu.org/files/projects/foiasearch/pdf/DOJFBI003584.pdf |title=Email &#91;parties redacted&#93; re: GTMO |date=2004 }}</ref><ref name="LAT-Miller">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/feb/24/nation/na-abuse24 |title=E-Mails Show FBI Agents Fretted About Prisoner Abuse |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=February 24, 2006 |first=Greg |last=Miller |accessdate=July 30, 2018 }}</ref>

The real FBI operative was concerned that DIA's harsh methods and impersonation of FBI agents would complicate the Bureau's ability to do its job properly, saying "The next time a real Agent tries to talk to that guy, you can imagine the result."<ref name="aclu.org"/> A subsequent military inquiry countered FBI's allegations by saying that the prisoner treatment was degrading but not inhuman, without addressing the allegation of DIA staff regularly impersonating FBI officers - usually a [[felony]] offense.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Neil |authorlink=Neil Lewis (journalist) |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/14/politics/14gitmo.html |title=Report Discredits F.B.I. Claims of Abuse at Guantánamo Bay |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 14, 2005 |accessdate=July 30, 2018 }}</ref> A year before this investigation was concluded, it was revealed that interrogations by [[Task Force 6-26|special units]] of the U.S. military services were much harsher and more physical than any of the above DIA practices, to the point that 2 DIA officials reportedly complained, after which they were threatened by non-DIA interrogators.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Neil |authorlink=Neil Lewis (journalist) |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/07/politics/07cnd-abus.html |title=Memos Say 2 Officials Who Saw Prison Abuse Were Threatened |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 7, 2004 |accessdate=July 30, 2018 }}</ref>

Similar activities are thought to have transpired at the hands of DIA operatives in [[Bagram]], where as recently as 2010 the organization ran the so-called "[[Black jail]]". According to a report published by [[The Atlantic]], the jail was manned by DIA's [[DCHC]] staff, who were accused of beating and sexually humiliating high-value targets held at the site.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ambinder |first=Marc |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2010/05/inside-the-secret-interrogation-facility-at-bagram/56678/ |title=Inside the Secret Interrogation Facility at Bagram |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=May 14, 2010 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref> The detention center outlived the black sites ran by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]], with the DIA allegedly continuing to use "restricted" interrogation methods in the facility under a secret authorization. It is unclear what happened to the secret facility after the 2013 transfer of the base to Afghan authorities following several postponements.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alex |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/mar/25/world/la-fg-wn-us-bagram-prison-afghanistan-20130325 |title=U.S. hands over control of Bagram prison to Afghan government |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=March 25, 2013 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref>

===U.S. Armed Forces===
[[File:Abu Ghraib 56.jpg|thumb|230 px|right|An Army investigator counted the use of unmuzzled dogs at [[Abu Graib]] as among the "sadistic, blatant, and wanton criminal abuses" by U.S. troops.<ref>{{Cite news |authorlink=R. Jeffrey Smith |first=R. Jeffrey |last=Smith |title=General Is Said To Have Urged Use of Dogs |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A55703-2004May25.html |quote= |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=May 26, 2004 |accessdate=January 23, 2014 }}</ref>]]
The following techniques were authorized by the U.S. military:<ref name="SERE"/><ref name="GitmoMyth">{{cite news |authorlink=Arthur L. Herman |last=Herman |first=Arthur |url=https://www.commentarymagazine.com/american-society/the-gitmo-myth-and-the-torture-canard/ |title=The Gitmo Myth and the Torture Canard |work=[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]] |date=May 21, 2009 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite report |url=http://www.dodig.mil/fo/Foia/ERR/06-INTEL-10-part%201.pdf |title=Review of DoD-Directed Investigations of Detainee Abuse |work=[[Office of the Inspector General, U.S. Department of Defense]] |date=August 25, 2006 |archivedate=February 28, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228192739/http://www.dodig.mil/fo/Foia/ERR/06-INTEL-10-part%201.pdf |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref>
