|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/01/national/nationalspecial3/01gitmo.html
}}
</ref>

On July 12, 2005, members of a military panel told the committee that they proposed disciplining prison commander [[Major General]] [[Geoffrey D. Miller|Geoffrey Miller]] over the interrogation of [[Mohammed al Qahtani]], who was forced to wear a [[bra]], dance with another man, and threatened with dogs. The recommendation was overruled by General [[Bantz J. Craddock]], commander of [[U.S. Southern Command]], who referred the matter to the army's inspector general.<ref>{{Cite news| date=July 13, 2005| url=http://www.cnn.com/2005/POLITICS/07/13/senate.guantanao.ap/index.html| title=Investigators recommended disciplining Gitmo commander| publisher=CNN.com| accessdate = 2006-03-19 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20050716010124/http://www.cnn.com/2005/POLITICS/07/13/senate.guantanao.ap/index.html |archivedate = 2005-07-16}}</ref>

In an interview with AP on February 14, 2008, [[Paul Rester]], chief military interrogator at Guantanamo Bay and director of the Joint Intelligence Group, said most of the information gathered from detainees came from non-coercive questioning and "rapport building", not harsh interrogation methods.<ref name="Paul Rester">{{cite web |url=https://www.jurist.org/news/2008/02/chief-guantanamo-interrogator-says-most/ |title=Chief Guantanamo interrogator says most info not forced from detainees |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180805132410/https://www.jurist.org/news/2008/02/chief-guantanamo-interrogator-says-most/ |archivedate=August 5, 2018 |first=Eric |last=Firkel |work=[[JURIST]] |date=February 17, 2008 }}</ref>

==Initial reports and complaints==
In 2006, senior [[Law enforcement agency|law enforcement]] agents with the [[Criminal Investigation Task Force]] told [[MSNBC.com]] that they began to complain in 2002 inside the [[United States Department of Defense|U.S. Department of Defense]] that the interrogation tactics used in [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay]] by a separate team of [[military intelligence]] investigators were unproductive, not likely to produce reliable information, and probably illegal. Unable to get satisfaction from the army commanders running the detainee camp, they took their concerns to [[David Brant]], director of the [[Naval Criminal Investigative Service]] (NCIS), who alerted Navy General Counsel [[Alberto J. Mora]].<ref name="msnbc.msn.com">{{Cite web| url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/15361458/| title=Gitmo interrogations spark battle over tactics|date=October 23, 2006| accessdate = 2006-11-05}}</ref>

General Counsel Mora and Navy Judge Advocate General [[Michael Lohr]] believed the detainee treatment to be unlawful, and campaigned among other top lawyers and officials in the Defense Department to investigate, and to provide clear standards prohibiting coercive interrogation tactics.<ref name="newyorker.com">{{Cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/images/pdfs/moramemo.pdf| title=Memorandum for Inspector General, Department of the Navy. Statement for the record: Office of General Counsel involvement in interrogation issues| format=PDF| date=July 7, 2005| accessdate = 2006-03-19}}</ref> In response, on January 15, 2003, Rumsfeld suspended the approved interrogation tactics at Guantánamo Bay until a new set of guidelines could be produced by a working group headed by General Counsel of the Air Force [[Mary L. Walker|Mary Walker]].

The working group based its new guidelines on a legal memo from the [[United States Department of Justice]] [[Office of Legal Counsel]] written by [[John Yoo]] and signed by [[Jay S. Bybee]] in August 2002, which would later become widely known as the "[[Bybee memo|Torture Memo]]." General Counsel Mora led a faction of the Working Group in arguing against these standards, and argued the issues with Yoo in person. The working group's final report was signed and delivered to Guantánamo without the knowledge of Mora and the others who had opposed its content. Mora has maintained that detainee treatment has been consistent with the law since the January 15, 2003, suspension of previously approved interrogation tactics.<ref name="http">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/2004/12/13/tribunals-didnt-rely-on-torture/45b1560e-40b1-405a-b93e-bbc3fa2bbdb7/ |title=Tribunals Didn't Rely on Torture |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 13, 2004 |first=Alberto J. |last=Mora |authorlink=Alberto J. Mora }}</ref>

It was not known publicly until 2008 that Yoo wrote another legal opinion, dated March 14, 2003, which he issued to the General Counsel of DOD, five days before the invasion of Iraq started. In it, he concluded that federal laws related to torture and other abuse did not apply to interrogators overseas&nbsp;– which at that time the administration applied to Guantanamo as well as locations such as Iraq.{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}

==Public positions and reactions==
President Bush stated "The United States of America does not torture. And that's important for people around the world to understand."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2005/12/a-tortured-history/ |title=A Tortured History: The President says "We do not torture." We look at what has surfaced so far |work=[[FactCheck]] |date=December 19, 2005 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref> The administration adopted the [[Detainee Treatment Act of 2005]] to address the multitude of incidents of [[detainee abuse]]. However, in his [[signing statement]], Bush made clear that he reserved the right to waive this bill if he thought that was needed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/03/02/AR2006030202054_pf.html |title=U.S. Cites Exception in Torture Ban: McCain Law May Not Apply to Cuba Prison |authorlink=Josh White (journalist) |first=Josh |last=White |first2=Carol D. |last2=Leonnig |author2link=Carol D. Leonnig |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 3, 2006 |accessdate=August 6, 2018 |quote=Government lawyers have argued that another portion of that same law, the Detainee Treatment Act of 2005, removes general access to U.S. courts for all Guantanamo Bay captives. }}</ref><ref name="Bush_HR2863">{{cite news |last = Bush |first=George W. |date=December 30, 2005 |url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2005/12/print/20051230-8.html |title=President's Statement on Signing of H.R. 2863 |work=[[The White House]] |accessdate=April 25, 2009 |quote=Finally, ... noting that section 1005 does not confer any constitutional right upon an alien detained abroad as an enemy combatant, the executive branch shall construe section 1005 to preclude the Federal courts from exercising subject matter jurisdiction over any existing or future action, including applications for writs of habeas corpus, described in section 1005. }}</ref>

[[Porter Goss]], the Director of Central Intelligence, in testimony before the [[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services|Senate Armed Services Committee]] on March 17, 2005, described waterboarding as falling into the area of  "professional interrogation techniques," differentiating them from torture:<ref name="NYT31805">{{cite news|author1=Douglas Jehl|title=Questions Are Left by C.I.A. Chief on the Use of Torture|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/18/politics/questions-are-left-by-cia-chief-on-the-use-of-torture.html|accessdate=February 9, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=March 18, 2005}}</ref>

{{quote|As I said publicly before, and I know for a fact, that torture is not -- it's not productive," Mr. Goss said. "That's not professional interrogation. We don't do torture."<ref name="NYT31805"/>}}

''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported in January 2009 that [[Susan J. Crawford]], [[convening authority]] of military commissions, stated about the interrogation of [[Mohammed al-Qahtani]], one of the alleged "[[20th hijacker]]s" of the [[September 11 attacks]]:

<blockquote>The techniques they used were all authorized, but the manner in which they applied them was overly aggressive and too persistent.... You think of torture, you think of some horrendous physical act done to an individual. This was not any one particular act; this was just a combination of things that had a medical impact on him, that hurt his health. It was abusive and uncalled for. And coercive. Clearly coercive. It was that medical impact that pushed me over the edge [i.e., to call it torture].<ref name="Crawford">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/13/AR2009011303372.html |title=Guantanamo Detainee Was Tortured, Says Official Overseeing Military Trials |first=Bob |last=Woodward |authorlink=Bob Woodward |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=January 14, 2009 |accessdate=August 6, 2018 }}</ref></blockquote>

Crawford decided not to prosecute al-Qahtani because his treatment fell within the definition of torture, so evidence was tainted by it having been gained through coercion.<ref name="Crawford"/>
[[File:Rumsfeld-4 hours a day.png|thumb|Comment from [[Donald Rumsfeld]]: "I stand for 8–10 hours a day. Why is standing [by prisoners] limited to four hours?"]]

Former President Bush in his published memoirs<ref>{{Cite book | last = Bush |first = George | title = Decision Points 
|publisher = Crown ; Enfield |year =2010 |page = | isbn = 0-307-59061-5}}</ref> defends the utility of "enhanced interrogation" techniques and continues to assert that they are not torture.<ref name = "Downing Street Opposes Torture">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/nov/09/george-bush-memoirs-waterboarding |title=Waterboarding is torture, Downing Street confirms |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=November 9, 2010 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref>

Former President Obama, former Attorney General Holder, and Guantanamo military prosecutor Crawford have called the techniques torture.<ref name = "Obama & Holder on torture"/> The British government has determined the techniques would be classified as torture, and dismissed President Bush's claim to the contrary.<ref name = "Downing Street Opposes Torture"/><ref name="NYTBurns20100211">{{cite news |authorlink=John F. Burns |last=Burns |first=John F. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/11/world/europe/11britain.html |title=Britain Discloses Data on Ex-Detainee |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 10, 2010 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref> A report by [[Human Rights First]] (HRF) and [[Physicians for Human Rights]] (PHR) stated that these techniques constitute torture.<ref name="Physicians for Human Rights"/> They also cite the U.S. [[Office of the Inspector General]] report which concluded "SERE-type [[interrogation]] techniques constitute 'physical or mental torture and coercion under the [[Geneva conventions]].'<ref name="SERE"/> "A [[United Nations]] report denounced the US abuse of prisoners as tantamount to torture.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/4718724.stm |title=UN calls for Guantanamo closure |work=[[BBC News]] |date=February 16, 2006 |accessdate=August 6, 2018 }}</ref> The UN report called for cessation of the US-termed "enhanced interrogation" techniques, as the UN sees these methods as a form of torture. The UN report also admonishes against [[black sites|secret prisons]], the use of which, is considered to amount to torture as well and should be discontinued.<ref name="UNCATreport" />

In 2009, Paul Kane of ''The Washington Post'' said that the press was hesitant to define these techniques as torture, as it is a crime and nobody who engaged in "enhanced interrogation" has been charged or convicted.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kane |first=Paul |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/discussion/2009/04/20/DI2009042001945.html |title=Post Politics: Congressional Investigations, Pelosi and Harman, More |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=April 23, 2009 |accessdate=August 16, 2018 }}</ref> ''The New York Times'' terms the techniques "harsh" and "brutal" while avoiding the word "torture" in most but not all<ref name="NYTimes2009-03-28">''The New York Times'' did call the treatment of prisoners at Guantanamo Bay torture in articles discussing the possibility of prosecution of Bush administration officials in Spain.{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/29/world/europe/29spain.html |title=Spanish Court Weighs Inquiry on Torture for 6 Bush-Era Officials |date=March 28, 2009 |first=Marlise |last=Simons |authorlink=Marlise Simons |work=[[The New York Times]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727212556/https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/29/world/europe/29spain.html |archivedate=July 27, 2018 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> news articles,<ref name="NYTHoyt20090426">{{cite news |last=Hoyt |first=Clark |authorlink=Clark Hoyt |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/26/opinion/26pubed.html |title=Telling the Brutal Truth |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 25, 2009 |accessdate=August 5, 2018 }}</ref> though it routinely identifies "enhanced interrogation" as torture in editorials.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/27/opinion/27fri1.html |title=Legacy of Torture |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 26, 2010 |accessdate=August 5, 2018 }}</ref> ''Slate'' magazine terms enhanced interrogation the "U.S. torture program."<ref>{{cite news |last=Lithwick |first=Dahlia |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/jurisprudence/2011/08/getting_away_with_torture.html |title=Getting Away With Torture |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=August 30, 2011 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 }}</ref>

In the summer of 2009, [[NPR]] decided to ban using the word torture<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.salon.com/2009/07/02/npr_2/ |title=The still-growing NPR "torture" controversy |work=[[Salon.com]] |date=July 2, 2009 |accessdate=July 27, 2018 |archivedate=April 15, 2012 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415083227/https://www.salon.com/2009/07/02/npr_2/ }}</ref> in what was a controversial act. Its Ombudsman Alicia Shepard's defense of the policy was that "calling waterboarding torture is tantamount to taking sides."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.onthemedia.org/transcripts/2009/06/26/02 |title=Torturous Wording |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704115001/http://www.onthemedia.org/transcripts/2009/06/26/02 |archivedate=2009-07-04 |publisher=[[NPR]] |work=[[On the Media]] |date=June 26, 2009 |accessdate=August 5, 2018 }}</ref> However, [[UC Berkeley School of Information|Berkeley]] Professor of Linguistics, [[Geoffrey Nunberg]], pointed out that virtually all media around the world, other than what he called the "spineless U.S. media", call these techniques torture.<ref>{{cite news |archivedate=June 8, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100608082952/http://www.scpr.org/programs/patt-morrison/2009/06/26/calling-a-spade-a-spade-use-of-the-word-torture/ |url=https://www.scpr.org/programs/patt-morrison/2009/06/26/729/calling-a-spade-a-spade-use-of-the-word-torture/ |title=Calling a Spade a Spade: Use of the Word 'Torture' |work=[[KPCC (radio station)|KPCC]] |date=June 26, 2009 |accessdate=July 24, 2018 |first=Patt |last=Morrison |authorlink=Patt Morrison }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McQuaid |first=John |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cifamerica/2009/may/12/torture-new-york-times-washington-post |title=The semantics of torture |work=[[Comment is free|guardian.co.uk – Comment-is-free]] |date=May 13, 2009 |accessdate=}}</ref> In an article on the euphemisms invented by the media that also criticized NPR, [[Glenn Greenwald]] discussed the enabling "corruption of American journalism":

<blockquote>This active media complicity in concealing that our Government created a systematic torture regime, by refusing ever to say so, is one of the principal reasons it was allowed to happen for so long. The steadfast, ongoing refusal of our leading media institutions to refer to what the Bush administration did as "torture"&nbsp;– even in the face of more than 100 detainee deaths; the use of that term by a leading Bush official to describe what was done at Guantanamo; and the fact that media outlets frequently use the word "torture" to describe exactly the same methods when used by other countries --reveals much about how the modern journalist thinks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.salon.com/2009/06/06/nyt_5/ |title=The NYT's nice, new euphemism for torture |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon.com]] |date=June 6, 2009 |first=Glenn |last=Greenwald |authorlink=Glenn Greenwald |accessdate=July 24, 2018 }}</ref></blockquote>

===Effectiveness and reliability===

====Senate Intelligence Committee report ====
{{Main|Senate Intelligence Committee report on CIA torture}}
On December 9, 2014, [[United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence]] (SSCI) released a 525-page document containing the key findings and an executive summary, of their report into the CIA's Detention and Interrogation Program.<ref name = "Panel Faults CIA">{{Cite news |author=Matt Mazzetti |title=Panel Faults C.I.A. Over Brutality and Deceit in Terrorism Interrogations |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/10/world/senate-intelligence-committee-cia-torture-report.html |quote= |work=[[The New York Times]] |date= December 9, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-09 }}</ref> The remainder of the 6,000 page report remains classified.<ref name=NPR>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/04/03/298779799/senate-torture-report-takes-a-step-closer-to-becoming-public|title=Congress Clashes Over Release of CIA Torture Report|author=Lauren Hodges|date=8 December 2014|publisher=NPR News|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=GuardDec0814>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/05/top-senator-rejects-cia-torture-report-redactions-ahead-of-release|title=Top senator rejects CIA torture report redactions ahead of public release|author=Spencer Ackerman|authorlink=Spencer Ackerman|date=5 August 2014|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Here's What Dianne Feinstein Said About the Torture Report|url=http://time.com/3625560/torture-report-heres-what-dianne-feinstein-said/|publisher=Time Magazine|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> The report concluded that the interrogation techniques were far more vicious and widespread than the CIA had previously reported; that "brutality, dishonesty and seemingly arbitrary violence at times brought even [CIA] employees to moments of anguish."<ref name = "Senate Report on CIA Depravity">{{Cite news |author1=Greg Miller |author2=Adam Goldman |author3=Julie Tate |title=Senate report on CIA program details brutality, dishonesty|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/senate-report-on-cia-program-details-brutality-dishonesty/2014/12/09/1075c726-7f0e-11e4-9f38-95a187e4c1f7_story.html |quote= |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 10, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-10 }}</ref> The report said that CIA officials had deceived their superiors at the White House, members of Congress and even sometimes their peers about how the interrogation program was being run and what it had achieved.<ref name = "Senate Report on CIA Depravity"/>

The executive summary lists 20 key findings:<ref name="TheReportItself">{{cite web |url= http://www.intelligence.senate.gov/study2014/sscistudy1.pdf |title= '''Committee Study of the Central Intelligence Agency's Detention and Interrogation Program''', Foreword by Senate Select Committee on Intelligence Chairman Dianne Feinstein, Findings and Conclusions, Executive Summary. |publisher=''United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence'' |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209165504/http://www.intelligence.senate.gov/study2014/sscistudy1.pdf |archive-date=December 9, 2014 |deadurl = yes |accessdate=June 15, 2015 |quote = Declassification Revisions December 3, 2014 }}</ref>

# The CIA's use of its enhanced interrogation techniques was not an effective means of acquiring [[intelligence assessment|intelligence]] or gaining cooperation from detainees.
# The CIA's justification for the use of its enhanced interrogation techniques rested on inaccurate claims of their effectiveness.
# The interrogations of CIA detainees were brutal and far worse than the CIA represented to policymakers and others.
# The conditions of confinement for CIA detainees were harsher than the CIA had represented to policymakers and others.
# The CIA repeatedly provided inaccurate information to the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]], impeding a proper legal analysis of the CIA's Detention and Interrogation Program.
# The CIA has actively avoided or impeded congressional oversight of the program.
# The CIA impeded effective White House oversight and decision-making.
# The CIA's operation and management of the program complicated, and in some cases impeded, the national security missions of other [[United States Executive Branch|Executive Branch]] agencies.
# The CIA impeded oversight by the CIA's [[Office of Inspector General]].
# The CIA coordinated the release of classified information to the media, including inaccurate information concerning the effectiveness of the CIA's enhanced interrogation techniques.
# The CIA was unprepared as it began operating its Detention and Interrogation Program more than six months after being granted detention authorities.
# The CIA's management and operation of its Detention and Interrogation Program was deeply flawed throughout the program's duration, particularly so in 2002 and early 2003.
# Two contract psychologists devised the CIA's enhanced interrogation techniques and played a central role in the operation, assessments, and management of the CIA's Detention and Interrogation Program. By 2005, the CIA had overwhelmingly outsourced operations related to the program.
# CIA detainees were subjected to coercive interrogation techniques that had not been approved by the Department of Justice or had not been authorized by CIA Headquarters.
# The CIA did not conduct a comprehensive or accurate accounting of the number of individuals it detained, and held individuals who did not meet the legal standard for detention. The CIA's claims about the number of detainees held and subjected to its enhanced interrogation techniques were inaccurate.
# The CIA failed to adequately evaluate the effectiveness of its enhanced interrogation techniques.
# The CIA rarely reprimanded or held personnel accountable for serious or significant violations, inappropriate activities, and systematic and individual management failures.
# The CIA marginalized and ignored numerous internal critiques, criticisms, and objections concerning the operation and management of the CIA's Detention and Interrogation Program.
# The CIA's Detention and Interrogation Program was inherently unsustainable and had effectively ended by 2006 due to unauthorized press disclosures, reduced cooperation from other nations, and legal and oversight concerns.
# The CIA's Detention and Interrogation Program damaged the United States' standing in the world, and resulted in other significant monetary and non-monetary costs.

The Senate Report examined in detail specifically whether torture provided information helpful in locating Osama Bin Laden, and concluded that it did not, and that the CIA deliberately misled political leaders and the public in saying it had.<ref name = "Does Torture Work?">{{Cite news |author=Matt Apuzzo |author2=Haeyon Park |author3=Larry Buchannon  |title=Does Torture Work? The CIA's Claims and What the Committee Found |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/12/08/world/does-torture-work-the-cias-claims-and-what-the-committee-found.html |quote= |work=[[The New York Times]] |date= December 9, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-09 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |author=Adam Goldman |title=Senate report disputes CIA account of Osama bin Laden search|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/harsh-interrogation-techniques-detailed-in-report/2014/12/09/dd3173c4-7fd0-11e4-81fd-8c4814dfa9d7_story.html |quote= |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 10, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-10 }}</ref>

The three former CIA directors [[George Tenet]], [[Porter Goss]], and [[Michael Hayden (general)|Michael Hayden]], who had supervised the program during their tenure, objected to the Senate Report in a Wall Street Journal op-ed piece, calling it poorly done and partisan.<ref name = "Tenet, Goss & Hayden">{{Cite news |author1=George Tenet |author2=Porter Goss |author3=Michael Hayden |title=Ex-CIA Directors: Interrogations Saved Lives |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/cia-interrogations-saved-lives-1418142644 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=December 10, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-10 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> They insisted that some information derived from the CIA program was useful, specifically that interrogation techniques made some detainees compliant and that the "information provided by the totality of detainees in CIA custody" had  led to Osama Bin Laden.<ref name = "Tenet, Goss & Hayden"/> According to the CIA, enhanced interrogation "conditions" were used for security and "other valid reasons, such as to create an environment conducive to transitioning captured and resistant terrorist (sic) to detainees participating in debriefings." <ref>{{cite report |work=[[Senate Select Committee on Intelligence]] |title=Minority views of Vice Chairman Chambliss joined by Senators Burr, Risch, Coats, Rubio, and Coburn |date=June 20, 2014 |p=98 |url=http://templatelab.com/sscistudy3-2014/ |section=CIA Study Response, Conclusions (TAB B) |accessdate=February 12, 2015}}</ref>

Republican [[Senator John McCain]], citing Obama Administration CIA Director [[Leon Panetta]] (who did not join with the others in the Wall Street Journal Op-ed) had previously said that brutality produced no useful information in the hunt for Osama Bin Laden; leads were "obtained through standard, noncoercive means."<ref>{{cite news |last=McCain |first=John |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/bin-ladens-death-and-the-debate-over-torture/2011/05/11/AFd1mdsG_story.html |title=Bin Laden's death and the debate over torture |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=May 11, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2018 }}</ref> In May 2011, Panetta had written to Senator McCain, that:

{{quote| . . . we first learned about the facilitator/courier's nom de guerre from a detainee not in CIA custody in 2002. It is also important to note that some detainees who were subjected to enhanced interrogation techniques attempted to provide false or misleading information about the facilitator/courier. These attempts to falsify the facilitator/courier's role were alerting. In the end, no detainee in CIA custody revealed the facilitator/courier's full true name or specific whereabouts. This information was discovered through other intelligence means.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sargent|first=Greg|title=Exclusive: Private letter from CIA chief undercuts claim torture was key to killing Bin Laden |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/plum-line/post/exclusive-private-letter-from-cia-chief-undercuts-claim-torture-was-key-to-killing-bin-laden/2011/03/03/AFLFF04G_blog.html |accessdate=20 May 2011 |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=16 May 2011}}</ref>}}

In 2014, Panetta wrote that torture did produce some useful information, but that the product was not worth the price, and if asked whether America should engage in similar practices he would say "no."<ref>{{cite news |author=Walter Pincus |title=Coexistence of aggressive interrogation and civil liberties|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/coexistence-of-aggressive-interrogation-and-civil-liberties/2014/10/20/924517d6-56d5-11e4-ba4b-f6333e2c0453_story.html |quote= |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=October 20, 2014  |accessdate=2014-12-12 }}</ref>  Obama Administration CIA director [[John O. Brennan|John Brennan]] said that it is "unknowable" whether brutality helped or hindered in the collection of useful intelligence.<ref>{{cite news |author=Brian Murphy |title=CIA chief: 'Unknowable' whether ordinary interrogation would bring same intel gains
|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/cia-director-impossible-to-assess-gains-from-enhanced-interrogations/2014/12/11/8ba972e0-8160-11e4-9f38-95a187e4c1f7_story.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 11, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-11 }}</ref>  White House Press Secretary [[Josh Earnest]] said whether information derived from CIA torture may have helped find Osama Bin Laden, President Obama believes "the use of these techniques was not worth it because of the harm that was done to our national values and the sense of what we believe in as Americans."<ref>{{Cite news |author=John Earnest |title=Earnest to Karl: Even if Enhanced Interrogations Did Help Find bin Laden, It Wasn't Worth Damage It Did To US.|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2014/12/08/earnest_to_karl_even_if_enhanced_interrogation_did_help_find_bin_laden_it_wasnt_worth_damage_it_did_to_us.html |work=[[Real Clear Politics]] |date= December 9, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-09 }}</ref> Similarly, Republican McCain agreed with Democrat Dianne Feinstein in remarks on the Senate floor that torture "stained our national honor" and did "much harm and little practical good."<ref>{{Cite news |author=Alexandra Jaffe |title=McCain Comments on CIA Torture Report|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/12/09/politics/mccain-lauds-release-terror-report/index.html |quote= |work=[[CNN]] |date=December 9, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-10 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |author=Carolyn Lochhead |title=Feinstein report: CIA misled Bush, public about torture |url=http://www.sfgate.com/nation/article/Feinstein-report-CIA-misled-Bush-public-about-5945109.php |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=December 9, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-10 }}</ref>

==== CIA assessment on efficacy of EITs ====

On request by the [[National Security Advisor (United States)|National Security Advisor]] [[Susan Rice]] in 2015, the CIA compiled a summary of key intelligence, which according to their records had been collected after the application of (unspecified) interrogation techniques. The memorandum lists intelligence related to the following topics: The Karachi Plot, The Heathrow Plot, The "Second Wave", The Guraba Cell, Issa al-Hindi, Abu Talha al-Pakistani, [[Riduan Isamuddin|Hambali's Capture]], Jafaar al-Tayyar, [[Dirty bomb#Possibility of terrorist groups using dirty bombs|Dirty Bomb Plot]], [[Shoe bomber]], and Sh(a)kai (Pakistan). The CIA concluded that the enhanced interrogation techniques had been effective in providing intelligence and has been a key reason why al-Qa'ida has failed to launch a spectacular attack in the West since 11 September. 2001.<ref name="CIA000 6541535">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/document/6541535 | title= 
Effectiveness of the CIA counterterrorist interrogation techniques|publisher=CIA| date=13 June 2016}}</ref>

===Destruction of videotapes===
{{see also|2005 CIA interrogation tapes destruction}}
In December 2007 it became known that the CIA had destroyed many videotapes recording the interrogation of prisoners. Disclosures in 2010 revealed that [[Jose Rodriguez (intelligence officer)|Jose Rodriguez Jr.]], head of the directorate of operations at the CIA from 2004 to 2007, ordered the tapes destroyed because he thought they would be "devastating to the CIA", and that "the heat from destroying is nothing compared to what it would be if the tapes ever got into public domain."<ref>Finn, Peter and Tate, Juile [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/04/15/AR2010041505854.html 2005 Destruction of Interrogation Tapes Caused Concern at CIA, e-mails Show."] (quoting e-mail from aide to Rodriguez that "it would be 'devastating' to us."), ''The Washington Post'', April 15, 2010</ref> ''The New York Times'' reported that according to "some insiders," an inquiry into the [[C.I.A.'s secret detention program]] which analyzed these techniques, "might end with criminal charges for abusive interrogations."<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/30/washington/30intel.html |title=Tapes by C.I.A. Lived and Died to Save Image |first=Scott |last=Shane |authorlink=Scott Shane |first2=Mark |last2=Mazzetti |authorlink2=Mark Mazzetti |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 30, 2007 |accessdate=July 24, 2018 }}</ref> In an Op-ed for the ''New York Times,'' [[Thomas Kean|Thomas H. Kean]] and [[Lee H. Hamilton]], chair and vice chair of the [[9/11 Commission]], stated:

<blockquote>As a legal matter, it is not up to us to examine the C.I.A.'s failure to disclose the existence of these tapes. That is for others. What we do know is that government officials decided not to inform a lawfully constituted body, created by Congress and the president, to investigate one ''(of)'' the greatest tragedies to confront this country. We call that [[obstruction of justice|obstruction]].<ref name="Tom Kean and Lee Hamilton">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/02/opinion/02kean.html |title=Stonewalled by the C.I.A. |authorlink=Thomas Kean |first=Thomas H. |last=Kean |first2=Lee H. |last2=Hamilton |authorlink2=Lee H. Hamilton |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 2, 2008 |accessdate=July 24, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="Greenwald obstructed">{{cite news |url=https://www.salon.com/2008/01/02/obstruction/ |first=Glenn |last=Greenwald |authorlink=Glenn Greenwald |title=9/11 Commission: Our investigation was obstructed |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date=January 2, 2008 |accessdate=July 24, 2018 }}</ref></blockquote>

Responding to the so-called "torture memoranda" [[Scott Horton (lawyer)|Scott Horton]] noted:

<blockquote>the possibility that the authors of these memoranda counseled the use of lethal and unlawful techniques, and therefore face [[command responsibility|criminal culpability]] themselves. That, after all, is the teaching of [[United States v. Altstötter]], the Nuremberg case brought against German Justice Department lawyers whose memoranda crafted the basis for implementation of the infamous "[[Night and Fog Decree]].<ref name="The Return of Carl Schmitt"/></blockquote>

[[Jordan Paust]] concurred by responding to Mukasey's refusal to investigate and/or prosecute anyone that relied on these legal opinions

<blockquote>it is legally and morally impossible for any member of the executive branch to be acting lawfully or within the scope of his or her authority while following OLC opinions that are manifestly inconsistent with or violative of the law. General Mukasey, [[superior orders|just following orders]] is no defense!<ref name="Following orders">{{cite web |url=http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/forumy/2008/02/just-following-orders-doj-opinions-and.php |title=Just Following Orders? DOJ Opinions and War Crimes Liability |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090508105006/http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/forumy/2008/02/just-following-orders-doj-opinions-and.php |archivedate=2009-05-08 |first=Jordan |last=Paust |work=[[JURIST]] |date=February 18, 2008 |accessdate=July 29, 2018 }}</ref></blockquote>

===International Committee of the Red Cross report===
On March 15, 2009, [[Mark Danner]] provided a report in the ''[[New York Review of Books]]'' (with an abridged version in ''The New York Times'') describing and commenting on the contents of a report by the [[International Committee of the Red Cross]] (ICRC), ''Report on the Treatment of Fourteen "High Value Detainees" in CIA Custody'' (43&nbsp;pp., February 2007). ''Report... '' is a record of interviews with [[black site]] detainees, conducted between October 6 and 11 and December 4 and 14, 2006, after their transfer to Guantánamo.<ref name="ICRC report">ICRC report
*[http://www.nybooks.com/icrc-report.pdf ICRC Report on the Treatment of Fourteen "High Value Detainees" in CIA Custody] International Committee of the Red Cross, Regional Delegation for United States and Canada, February 14, 2007
*[http://www.nybooks.com/articles/22530 "US Torture: Voices from the Black Sites"] by Mark Danner, ''New York Review of Books'', April 9, 2009
*[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/15/opinion/15danner.html "Tales from Torture's Dark World"] by Mark Danner, ''The New York Times'', March 15, 2009</ref> (According to Danner, the report was marked "confidential" and was not previously made public before being made available to him.)

Danner provides excerpts of interviews with detainees, including Abu Zubaydah, [[Walid bin Attash]], and Khalid Sheikh Mohammed. According to Danner, the report contains sections on "methods of ill-treatment" including suffocation by water, prolonged stress standing, beatings by use of a collar, beating and kicking, confinement in a box, prolonged nudity, sleep deprivation and use of loud music, exposure to cold temperature/cold water, prolonged use of handcuffs and shackles, threats, forced shaving, and deprivation/restricted provision of solid food. Danner quotes the ICRC report as saying that, "in many cases, the ill-treatment to which they were subjected while held in the CIA program, either singly or in combination, constituted torture. In addition, many other elements of the ill-treatment, either singly or in combination, constituted cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment."<ref name="ICRC report"/>

A heavily redacted version of the November 8, 2006 meeting was released by the CIA on June 10, 2016. The report tells that the ICRC finds the detainees stories "largely credible, having put much stock in the fact that the story each detainee told about his transfer, treatment and conditions of confinement was basically consistent, even though they had been incommunicado with each other throughout their detention by us [the CIA]." <ref>{{cite report |author=John A Rizzo |editor= CIA|date=November 9, 2006 |title=8 November 2006 meeting with ICRC reps |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/document/6552081 |publisher= |page= |docket= 
F-2015-02400 |access-date=June 15, 2016 |quote= }}</ref>

===Senate Armed Services Committee report===
{{Main|Abu Ghraib torture and prisoner abuse}}
A bipartisan Senate Armed Services Committee report,<ref name=scasreport /> released in part in December 2008 and in full in April 2009, concluded that the legal authorization of "enhanced interrogation techniques" led directly to the abuse and killings of prisoners in US military facilities at Abu Ghraib, [[Bagram Airfield|Bagram]], and elsewhere.<ref name="Brutal Techniques Report">{{cite news |last=Knowlton |first=Brian |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/22/us/politics/22report.html |title=Report Gives New Detail on Approval of Brutal Techniques |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 21, 2009 }}</ref> Brutal abuse [[Mind control#Korean War brainwashing debunked|believed to originate in Chinese communist torture techniques to extract false confessions from American POWs]] migrated from Guantanamo Bay to Afghanistan, then to Iraq and Abu Ghraib.<ref>{{cite news |last=Chaddock |first=Gail Russell |url=https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/2009/0422/report-says-top-officials-set-tone-for-detainee-abuse |title=Report says top officials set tone for detainee abuse |work=[[Christian Science Monitor]] |date=April 22, 2009 |accessdate=July 30, 2018 }}</ref> The report concludes that some authorized techniques including "use of stress positions and sleep deprivation combined with other mistreatment" caused or were direct contributing factors in the cases of several prisoners who were "tortured to death."<ref>{{cite news |last=Greenwald |first=Glenn |authorlink=Glenn Greenwald |url=https://www.salon.com/2008/12/15/rumsfeld_2/ |title=Senate Report Links Bush to Detainee Homicides; Media Yawns |work=[[Salon.com]] |date=December 15, 2008 |accessdate=July 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name="The Public Record">{{cite news |url=http://pubrecord.org/torture/292/senate-panels-report-links-detainees-murders-to-bushs-torture-policy/ |title=Senate Panel's Report Links Detainees' Murders to Bush's Torture Policy |work=[[The Public Record]] |date=April 30, 2009 |accessdate=July 24, 2018 |first=Jason |last=Leopold |authorlink=Jason Leopold }}</ref><ref name="Rumsfeld to Blame">{{cite news |last=Barnes |first=Greg |last2=Miller |first2=Julian |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/dec/12/nation/na-interrogate-abuse12 |title=Senate Report Says Rumsfeld to Blame for Detainee Abuse |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=September 12, 2008 |accessdate=August 16, 2018 }}</ref> The report also notes that authorizing abuse created the conditions for other, unauthorized abuse, by creating a legal and moral climate encouraging inhumane treatment.<ref name="Rumsfeld to Blame"/> The legal memos condoning "enhanced interrogation" had "redefined torture",<ref name="Brutal Techniques Report"/> "distorted the meaning and intent of anti-torture laws, [and] rationalized the abuse of detainees",<ref name="Rumsfeld to Blame"/> conveying the message that "physical pressures and degradation were appropriate treatment."<ref name="The Public Record"/> What followed was an "erosion of standards dictating that detainees be treated humanely."<ref name="Brutal Techniques Report"/>{{rp|xxix}} The report accused Defense Secretary Rumsfeld and his deputies of being, according to ''The Washington Post'', directly responsible as the "authors and chief promoters of harsh interrogation policies that disgraced the nation and undermined U.S. security."<ref name="Washington Post on Report">{{cite news |last=Warrick |first=Joby |authorlink=Joby Warrick |last2=De Young |first2=Karen |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/12/11/AR2008121101969.html |title=Bipartisan Report on Detainee Abuse Blames Rumsfeld, Other Top Bush Officials |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 12, 2008 |accessdate=July 30, 2018 }}</ref>

===Comparison to the Gestapo interrogation method called 'Verschärfte Vernehmung'===
''[[Atlantic Monthly]]'' writer [[Andrew Sullivan]] has pointed out similarities between the [[Gestapo]] interrogation method called 'Verschärfte Vernehmung' and what the US called "enhanced interrogation".<ref name = "Verschärfte Vernehmung">{{cite news |last=Sullivan |first=Andrew |authorlink=Andrew Sullivan |url=http://andrewsullivan.theatlantic.com/the_daily_dish/2007/05/verschfte_verne.html |title="Verschärfte Vernehmung" |work=[[The Atlantic Monthly]] |date=29 May 2007 |accessdate=1 June 2018}}</ref> He asserts the first use of a term comparable to "enhanced interrogation" was a 1937 memo by Gestapo Chief [[Heinrich Müller (Gestapo)|Heinrich Müller]] coining the phrase "Verschärfte Vernehmung", German for "sharpened questioning", "intensified" or "enhanced interrogation" to describe subjection to extreme cold, sleep deprivation, suspension in stress positions, and deliberate exhaustion among other techniques.<ref name="Verschärfte Vernehmung"/> Sullivan reports that in 1948 Norway prosecuted German officials for what trial documents termed "Verschärfte Vernehmung" including subjection to cold water, and repeated beatings.<ref name="Verschärfte Vernehmung"/> Sullivan concludes:

<blockquote>The very phrase used by the president to describe torture-that-isn't-somehow-torture&nbsp;– "enhanced interrogation techniques"&nbsp;– is a term originally coined by the Nazis. The techniques are indistinguishable. The methods were clearly understood in 1948 as war-crimes. The punishment for them was death.<ref name="Verschärfte Vernehmung"/></blockquote>

==Investigation and calls for prosecution==

===Request for special counsel probe===
On June 8, 2008, fifty-six House Democrats asked for an independent investigation, raising the possibility that authorising these techniques may constitute a crime by Bush administration officials. The congressmen involved in calling for such an investigation included [[John Conyers]], [[Jan Schakowsky]], and [[Jerrold Nadler]].<ref name="Probe">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/06/07/AR2008060701194.html |title=Lawmakers Urge Special Counsel Probe of Harsh Interrogation Tactics |first=Joby |last=Warrick |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=June 8, 2008 |accessdate=July 24, 2018 }}</ref>

The letter was addressed to [[Attorney General]] [[Michael B. Mukasey]] observing that

<blockquote>information indicates that the Bush administration may have systematically implemented, from the top down, detainee interrogation policies that constitute torture or otherwise violate the law.<ref name="Probe"/></blockquote>

The letter continues to state:

<blockquote>Because these apparent 'enhanced interrogation techniques' were used under cover of Justice Department legal opinions, the need for an outside special prosecutor is obvious.<ref name="Probe"/></blockquote>

According to ''The Washington Post'' the request was denied because Attorney General Michael B. Mukasey felt that

<blockquote>officials acted in "good faith" when they sought legal opinions, and that the lawyers who provided them used their best judgment.<ref name="Carrie Johnson">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/07/10/AR2008071002749.html "Mukasey Rejects Inquiry"] Carrie Johnson, ''The Washington Post'', July 11, 2008</ref></blockquote>

The article also reported that

<blockquote>He warned that criminalizing the process could cause policymakers to second-guess themselves and "harm our national security well into the future."<ref name="Carrie Johnson"/></blockquote>

After Cheney acknowledged his involvement in authorising these tactics<ref name="Cheney on report">{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/Story?id=6464697&page=2 |title=Transcript: Cheney Defends Hard Line Tactics |work=[[ABC News]] |date=December 15, 2008 |accessdate=July 24, 2018 }}</ref> Senator [[Carl Levin]], chair of the Armed Services Committee, a New York Times editorial, Glenn Greenwald and Scott Horton stressed the importance of a [[criminal investigation]]:

<blockquote>A prosecutor should be appointed to consider criminal charges against top officials at the Pentagon and others involved in planning the abuse.<ref name="Special prosecutor">War crimes investigation warranted
*[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/18/opinion/18thu1.html "The Torture Report"] Editorial, ''The New York Times'', December 17, 2008
*[http://harpers.org/archive/2008/12/hbc-90004041 "NYT: Prosecute the Torture Team] by Scott Horton, No Comment, ''Harper's Magazine'', December 18, 2008
*[http://harpers.org/archive/2008/12/hbc-90004040 "Levin Discusses Need for Torture Prosecutions"] by Scott Horton, No Comment, ''Harper's Magazine'', December 17, 2008
*{{cite news |url=http://www.salon.com/2008/12/18/prosecutions/ |title=Demands for war crimes prosecutions are now growing in the mainstream |first=Glenn |last=Greenwald |authorlink=Glenn Greenwald |work=[[Salon.com]] |date=December 18, 2008 }}</ref></blockquote>

===United Nations Convention Against Torture===
Shortly before the end of Bush's second term, news media in other countries were opining that under the [[United Nations Convention Against Torture]], the U.S. is obligated to hold those responsible to account under [[criminal law]].<ref name="Calls for prosecution">{{cite news |url=https://harpers.org/blog/2009/01/overseas-expectations-build-for-torture-prosecutions/ |title=Overseas, Expectations Build for Torture Prosecutions |first=Scott |last=Horton |authorlink=Scott Horton (attorney) |work=[[Harper's Magazine]], ''No Comment'' |date=January 19, 2009 |accessdate=July 24, 2018 }}</ref>

The United Nations Special Rapporteur on torture and other cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment or punishment, Professor [[Manfred Nowak]], on January 20, 2009, remarked on German television that, following the inauguration of [[Barack Obama]] as new President, George W. Bush has lost his [[head of state immunity]] and under international law, the U.S. is now mandated to start criminal proceedings against all those involved in these violations of the UN Convention Against Torture.<ref name="Nowak">Special Rapporteur on torture and other cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment or punishment calls for prosecution
*[http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/paperchase/2009/01/un-torture-investigator-calls-on-obama.php "UN torture investigator calls on Obama to charge Bush for Guantanamo abuses"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502015654/http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/paperchase/2009/01/un-torture-investigator-calls-on-obama.php |date=May 2, 2009 }} Ximena Marinero, JURIST, January 21, 2009
*[http://harpers.org/archive/2009/01/hbc-90004250 "UN Rapporteur: Initiate criminal proceedings against Bush and Rumsfeld now"] by Scott Horton, ''No Comment'', January 21, 2009</ref> Law professor Dietmar Herz explained Nowak's comments by saying that under U.S. and international law former President Bush is criminally responsible for adopting torture as an interrogation tool.<ref name="Nowak"/>

===Binyam Mohamed case===
On February 4, 2009, the [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] of [[England and Wales]] ruled that evidence of possible torture in the case of [[Binyam Mohamed]], an Ethiopian-born British resident who was held in Guantanamo Bay until 2009, could not be disclosed to the public:

<blockquote>as a result of a statement by [[David Miliband]], the [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]], that if the evidence was disclosed the US would stop sharing intelligence with Britain. That would directly threaten the UK's national security, Miliband had told the court.<ref name="Preventing international investigation">Investigation by other countries obstructed
*[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/feb/04/guantanamo-torture/print "US threats mean evidence of British resident's Guantánamo torture must stay secret, judges rule Tory MP David Davis demands urgent Commons statement on MI5 role in Binyam Mohamed case"], Richard Norton-Taylor, ''[[The Guardian]]'', Wednesday February 4, 2009
*[http://harpers.org/archive/2009/02/hbc-90004343 "Bush Administration Threatened Britain Over Torture Disclosures"] by Scott Horton, ''Harper's'', February 4, 2009</ref></blockquote>

The judges said they found it "difficult to conceive" the rationale for the US's objections to releasing the information, which contained "no disclosure of sensitive intelligence matters". Adding, "we did not consider that a democracy governed by the rule of law would expect a court in another democracy to suppress a summary of the evidence contained in reports by its own officials".<ref name="Preventing international investigation"/>

Responding to the ruling, [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]], the Conservative MP and former [[Shadow Home Secretary]], commented:

<blockquote>The ruling implies that torture has taken place in the <nowiki>[Binyam]</nowiki> Mohamed case, that British agencies may have been complicit, and further, that the United States government has threatened our high court that if it releases this information the US government will withdraw its intelligence cooperation with the United Kingdom.<ref name="Preventing international investigation"/></blockquote>

The High Court judges also stated in 2009, that a criminal investigation, by the UK's [[Law Officers of the Crown|Attorney General]], into possible torture had begun.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7870049.stm |title=Ministers face torture pressure |work=[[BBC News]] |date=February 4, 2009 |accessdate=August 5, 2018 }}</ref>

In February 2010, the [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|UK Court of Appeal]] ruled that material held by the UK Foreign Secretary must be made public. The judges also concluded that Binyam Mohamed had been subjected to "cruel, inhuman and degrading treatment by the United States authorities" and that [[MI5|British Intelligence]] knew that Mohamed was being tortured by the CIA.<ref name="Court of appeal">{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/terrorism-in-the-uk/7204741/MI5-knew-Guantanamo-detainee-Binyam-Mohamed-was-being-tortured.html | title=MI5 knew Guantanamo detainee Binyam Mohamed was being tortured | publisher=''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' | date=10 February 2010 | accessdate=16 June 2015 |author1=Gardham, Duncan  |author2=Rayner, Gordon}}</ref>

==Legality==
After the disclosure of the use of the techniques, debates arose over the legality of the techniques—whether they had violated U.S. or international law.

===U.S. government===
{{Main|Torture memos}}
[[File:John-Yoo.jpg|right|thumb|[[John Yoo]], author of the "[[torture memos]]"]]
Following the [[September 11 attacks]] in 2001, several memoranda analyzing the legality of various interrogation methods<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB127/ |title=The Interrogation Documents: Debating U.S. Policy and Methods |date=July 13, 2004 }}</ref> were written by [[John Yoo]] from the [[Office of Legal Counsel]]. The memos, known today as the [[torture memos]],<ref name="The Return of Carl Schmitt">Suggested origin of legal justifications
*[http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=942865 "The Bush Regime from Elections to Detentions: A Moral Economy of Carl Schmitt and Human Rights"] by Abraham, David, University of Miami – School of Law, University of Miami Legal Studies Research Paper No. 2007-20 May 2007
*[http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=870602 "Torture, Necessity and Existential Politics"] by Kutz, Christopher L., [[University of California]], Berkeley – School of Law (Boalt Hall), UC Berkeley Public Law Research Paper No. 870602, December 2005
*[http://harpers.org/archive/2008/01/hbc-90002226 "Deconstructing John Yoo"] by Scott Horton, ''Harpers'', January 23, 2008
*[http://mondediplo.com/2006/09/08democracy "The will to undemocratic power"] By Philip S Golub, ''[[Le Monde Diplomatique]]'', September 2006
*[http://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel/0,1518,259860,00.html "The Leo-conservatives"] by Gerhard Spörl, ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', August 4, 2003</ref><ref name="Torture Memos">Yoo memos referred to as "torture memos"
*[http://www.law.berkeley.edu/news/2008/edley041008.html "The Torture Memos and Academic Freedom"] by [[Christopher Edley Jr.]], The Honorable [[William H. Orrick Jr.]] Distinguished Chair and Dean of UC Berkeley School of Law, [[Boalt Hall]], April 10, 2008
*[https://www.aclu.org/safefree/general/34879prs20080412.html "Bush Admits To Knowledge of Torture Authorization by Top Advisers"] by the [[ACLU]]
*[http://harpers.org/archive/2008/04/hbc-90002785 "Yoo Two"], by Scott Horton, ''No Comment'', April 3, 2008
*{{cite news |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080414030444/http://www.salon.com/opinion/greenwald/2008/04/12/yoo/index.html |archivedate=April 14, 2008 |url=http://www.salon.com/opinion/greenwald/2008/04/12/yoo/index.html |title=John Yoo: Spearhead or scapegoat? |authorlink=Glenn Greenwald |first=Glenn |last=Greenwald |date=April 12, 2008 }}</ref> advocate enhanced interrogation techniques, while pointing out that avoiding the Geneva Conventions would reduce the possibility of prosecution under the US [[War Crimes Act of 1996]] for actions taken in the [[War on Terror]].<ref>War crimes warning
*[http://www.newsweek.com/id/105057 "Memos Reveal War Crimes Warnings"] by Michael Isikoff, ''[[Newsweek]]'', May 19, 2004
*[http://www.thenation.com/doc/20050718/holtzman "Torture and Accountability"] by Elizabeth Holtzman, ''The Nation'', June 28, 2005
*[http://www.globalpolicy.org/security/issues/iraq/attack/law/2003/0128uslawyers.htm "US Lawyers Warn Bush on War Crimes"] by Grant McCool, [[Lawyers Against the War]], [[Global Policy Forum]], January 28, 2003</ref> In addition, a new US definition of torture was issued. Most actions that fall under the international definition do not fall within this new definition advocated by the U.S.<ref>US definition of torture
*[https://www.theguardian.com/guantanamo/story/0,,1711833,00.html "Judge's anger at US torture"] by Richard Norton-Taylor and Suzanne Goldenberg, ''The Guardian'', February 17, 2006
*[http://www.newyorker.com/images/pdfs/moramemo.pdf "Memorandum for Inspector General, Department of the Navy"] July 7, 2004
*[http://www.newyorker.com/fact/content/?060227fa_fact 2THE MEMO -How an internal effort to ban the abuse and torture of detainees was thwarted"] by JANE MAYER, ''The New Yorker'', February 20, 2006</ref>

The Bush administration told the CIA in 2002 that its interrogators working abroad would not violate US prohibitions against torture unless they "have the specific intent to inflict severe pain or suffering", according to a previously secret [[US Justice Department]] memo released on July 24, 2008. The interrogator's "good faith" and "honest belief" that the interrogation will not cause such suffering protects the interrogator, the memo adds. "Because specific intent is an element of the offense, the absence of specific intent negates the charge of torture", [[Jay Bybee]], then the [[Assistant Attorney General]], wrote in the memo dated August 1, 2002, addressed to the CIA acting General Counsel [[John A. Rizzo]]. The 18-page memo is heavily redacted, with 10 of its 18 pages completely blacked out and only a few paragraphs legible on the others.

Another memo released on the same day advises that "the [[waterboarding|waterboard]]", does "not violate the Torture Statute." It also cites a number of warnings against torture, including statements by President Bush and a then-new Supreme Court ruling "which raises possible concerns about future US [[judicial review]] of the [interrogation] Program."

A third memo instructs interrogators to keep records of sessions in which "enhanced interrogation techniques" are used. The memo is signed by then-CIA director [[George Tenet]] and dated January 28, 2003.

The memos were made public by the [[American Civil Liberties Union]], which obtained the three CIA-related documents under [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] requests.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/07/24/cia.torture/index.html |title=Previously secret torture memo released |work=[[CNN]] |date=July 24, 2008 |accessdate=July 24, 2018 }}</ref> They were among nearly 140,000 formerly classified documents from the Department of Defense, the Justice Department, and the CIA that provide details on the treatment of prisoners in U.S. custody in the "War on Terror" gathered by the ACLU.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/politics/2012/04/george_w_bush_and_torture_america_s_highest_officials_are_responsible_for_the_enhanced_interrogation_of_prisoners_.single.html |title=How America Came To Torture Its Prisoners |date=April 20, 2012 |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |author=Larry Siems}}</ref>

The less redacted version of the August 1, 2002, memo signed by [[Assistant Attorney General]] [[Jay Bybee]] (regarding [[Abu Zubaydah]]) and four memos from 2005 signed by Principal Deputy Assistant Attorney General [[Steven G. Bradbury]] addressed to CIA and analysing the legality of various specific interrogation methods, including waterboarding, were released by [[Barack Obama]]'s administration on April 16, 2009<ref>{{cite news |last=Abrams |first=Joseph |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/04/28/despite-reports-khalid-sheikh-mohammed-waterboarded-times/ |title=Despite Reports, Khalid Sheikh Mohammed Was Not Waterboarded 183 Times |work=[[Fox News]] |date=April 28, 2009 }}</ref>

Following the release of the CIA documents, [[Philip Zelikow]], a former State Department lawyer and adviser to then-Secretary of State [[Condoleezza Rice]], said that in 2005, he had written a legal memo objecting to torture. In it he argued that it was unlikely that "any federal court would agree (that the approval of harsh interrogation techniques) ... was a reasonable interpretation of the Constitution." He claimed that the Bush Administration had ordered all copies of his legal memo be collected and destroyed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=103396848 |title=Was Critical Note Muzzled By Bush White House? |work=[[NPR]] |date=April 23, 2009 |accessdate=July 24, 2018 |first=Scott |last=Neuman}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2009/04/21/the-olc-torture-memos-thoughts-from-a-dissenter/ |authorlink=Philip Zelikow |first=Philip |last=Zelikow |title=The OLC "torture memos": thoughts from a dissenter |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |date=April 21, 2009 |accessdate=July 24, 2018 }}</ref>

====Subsequent torture memoranda====
[[File:Steven G. Bradbury 2013-07-27.png|thumb|right|Steven G. Bradbury]]
In May 2005, in response to requests from the CIA, Bradbury authored several memoranda that confirmed that several so-called "enhanced interrogation techniques" did not constitute torture, including [[waterboarding]],<ref name=rough>{{cite news |last=Eggen |first=Dan |date=2008-02-17 |title=Justice Official Defends Rough CIA Interrogations |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/02/16/AR2008021602634.html |newspaper=Washington Post |access-date=2017-02-02 }}</ref> [[walling]], [[stress positions]], striking a prisoner,<ref name=Mazzetti /><ref name=latimes2007-10-06>{{cite news |last1= Miller |first=Greg |last2=Schmitt |first2=Richard B. |date=2007-10-06 |title=CIA doesn't use torture, Bush says |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/oct/06/nation/na-torture6 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=2016-07-10}}</ref><ref name=rough /> exposure to extreme temperatures,<ref name="NYT-2008-01-24">{{cite news |last1=Shenon |first1=Philip |last2=Lichtblau |first2=Eric |authorlink2=Eric Lichtblau |date=2008-01-24 |title=Justice Nomination Seen as Snub to Democrats |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/24/washington/24justice.html?_r=0 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=2015-12-28 }}</ref><ref name=latimes2007-10-06 /> dousing with cold water,<ref name="Salon20100309" /> and forced [[sleep deprivation]] of up to 180 hours ({{frac|7|1|2}} days),<ref name="Salon20100309">{{cite web | url=https://www.salon.com/2010/03/09/waterboarding_for_dummies/ |date=2010-03-09 | title=Waterboarding for dummies | author=Mark Benjamin | quote=Principal Deputy Assistant Attorney General Steven Bradbury wrote in a May 10, 2005, memo authorizing continued use of waterboarding }}</ref><ref name=memo10May2005-1 >{{cite web
| title=Memorandum for John Rizzo
| url=http://media.luxmedia.com/aclu/olc_05102005_bradbury46pg.pdf
| first=Steven G. | last=Bradbury
| publisher=ACLU
| date=May 10, 2005| accessdate=October 24, 2011}}</ref><ref name=memo10May2005-2 >{{cite web
| title=Memorandum for John Rizzo
| url=http://media.luxmedia.com/aclu/olc_05102005_bradbury_20pg.pdf
| first=Steven G. | last=Bradbury
| publisher=ACLU
| date=May 10, 2005| accessdate=October 24, 2011}}</ref><ref name=ThinkProgress>{{cite web |url=http://thinkprogress.org/politics/2007/10/16/16982/durbin-bradbury/ |title=Durbin, Feingold, Kennedy Demand Bush Withdraw Nominee For DOJ Office Of Legal Counsel |last1=Khanna |first1=Satyam |date=2007-10-16 |website=[[ThinkProgress]] |access-date=2015-12-26}}</ref><ref name=memo30May2005 >{{cite web
| title=Memorandum for John Rizzo
| url=http://media.luxmedia.com/aclu/olc_05302005_bradbury.pdf
| first=Steven G. | last=Bradbury
| publisher=ACLU
| date=May 30, 2005| accessdate=October 24, 2011}}</ref><ref name=time>{{cite news |last=Scherer |first=Michael |date=2009-04-21 |title=Scientists Claim CIA Misused Work on Sleep Deprivation |url=http://content.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1892897,00.html |newspaper=[[TIME]] |access-date=2017-02-02 }}</ref> even when used in combination.<ref name="Savage-2012-09-27">{{cite news |last=Savage |first=Charlie |authorlink=Charlie Savage |date=2012-09-27 |title=Election to Decide Future Interrogation Methods in Terrorism Cases |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/28/us/politics/election-will-decide-future-of-interrogation-methods-for-terrorism-suspects.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=2016-08-28 }}</ref><ref name=Stich>{{cite book |last=Stich |first=Rodney |date= |title=Iraq, Lies, Cover-Ups, and Consequences |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nWKikbvZzxIC&pg=PA262#v=onepage&q&f=false |publisher=Silverpeak Enterprises |page=262 |isbn=978-0932438225 |quote=In early 2005, over the objections of Mr. Comey, Steven G. Bradbury&mdash;appointed acting head in February 2005&mdash;signs a secret opinion that justifies combining different interrogation techniques. Mr. Bradbury is formally nominated for the permanent job in June 2005, but Democrats block his confirmation.}}</ref> These memoranda found the CIA's practices to be lawful if applied in accordance with specified conditions, limitations, and safeguards, including those set forth in the agency's interrogation procedures.<ref name="Mazzetti">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/17/us/politics/17detain.html |title=Interrogation Memos Detail Harsh Tactics by the C.I.A. |authorlink=Mark Mazzetti |author1=Mark Mazzetti |author2=Scott Shane |authorlink2=Scott Shane |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 16, 2009| accessdate=April 17, 2009}}</ref> Bradbury's memoranda were described by Democrats as an attempt to sidestep anti-torture laws and subvert a 2004 public Justice Department legal opinion characterizing torture as "abhorrent".<ref name="NYT-2008-01-24" /> These memoranda were publicly released by the Obama Administration on April 16, 2009.

Bradbury authored an additional memo dated July 2007, seeking to reconcile the interrogation techniques with new developments, including intervening legislation such as the [[Military Commissions Act of 2006]] and the December 2005 [[Detainee Treatment Act]]. In response to this and other new legislation, the 2007 memo provided legal authorization and OLC approval for a more limited set of actions for use when interrogating high-value detainees. This approval encompassed six listed techniques, including temporary food deprivation (no less than 1,000 calories/day), sleep deprivation by being forced to hold a "standing position for as many as four days", and several types of physical striking.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/nation/documents/2007_0720_OLC_memo_warcrimesact.pdf | date=2009-09-03 | title=MEMORANDUM FOR JOHN A. RIZZO ACTING GENERAL COUNSEL, CENTRAL INTELLIGENCE AGENCY Re: Application of the War Crimes Act, the Detainee Treatment Act, and Common Article 3 of the Geneva Conventions to Certain Techniques that May Be Used by the CIA in the Interrogation of High Value al Qaeda Detainees | author= Steven G. Bradbury | publisher=[[United States Department of Justice]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Eviatar |first=Daphne |date=2009-08-27 |title=Memos Suggest Legal Cherry-Picking in Justifying Torture: DOJ Lawyers' Analysis Changed Little Despite New Legal Backdrop |url=http://washingtonindependent.com/56772/memos-suggest-legal-cherry-picking-in-justifying-torture |dead-url=yes |newspaper=[[Washington Independent]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829054657/http://washingtonindependent.com/56772/memos-suggest-legal-cherry-picking-in-justifying-torture |archive-date=2009-08-29 |access-date=2015-12-28 }}</ref>

The cumulative effect of Bush administration legal memos and exemption from prosecution had been to create a "law free zone" according to the former Chief Prosecutor at Guantánamo, where civilian politicians expected the military to use torture "against our will and judgment."<ref>{{cite news |author=Ed Vulliamy |title=Former US chief prosecutor condemns 'law-free zone' of Guantánamo |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/oct/30/guantanamo-morris-davis |quote= |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=October 29, 2011 |accessdate=2014-12-16 }}</ref>

===International legal bodies===
On May 19, 2006, the [[UN Committee against Torture]] issued a report stating the U.S. should stop secretly detaining, torturing, and ill-treating terror suspects, since such treatment is illegal under international law.<ref name="UNCATreport">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/4996798.stm |title=US 'must end secret detentions' |work=[[BBC News]] |date=May 19, 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/un-us-should-close-gitmo/ |title=U.N.: U.S. Should Close Gitmo Panel On Torture Also Says U.S. Should Avoid Using Secret Prisons |work=[[CBS News]] |date=May 19, 2006 }}</ref>

In July 2014, the [[European Court of Human Rights]] condemned the government of Poland for participating in CIA [[extraordinary rendition]] to a [[black site]] in Poland for enhanced interrogation, which the court called "torture, inhumane and degrading treatment."<ref name= "European Court of Human Rights"/> The court ordered the government of Poland to pay restitution to men who had been tortured there.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Dan Bilesfsky |title=Court Censures Poland Over C.I.A. Renditions
|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/25/world/europe/europe-poland-cia-black-site-extraordinary-rendition.html |quote= |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 24, 2014 |accessdate=2014-10-26 }}</ref>

===Human rights organizations===
A report by Human Rights First (HRF) and [[Physicians for Human Rights]] (PFH) stated that these techniques constitute torture.<ref name="Physicians for Human Rights"/> Their press release said:

<blockquote>The report concludes that each of the ten tactics is likely to violate U.S. laws, including the [[War Crimes Act of 1996|War Crimes Act]], the [[U.S. Torture Act]], and the [[Detainee Treatment Act of 2005]].<ref name="Physicians for Human Rights">[[Human Rights First]] (HRF) and [[Physicians for Human Rights]] (PFH) report
*{{cite web |url=http://physiciansforhumanrights.org/library/news-2007-08-02.html |title=Those Who Authorize and Use CIA "Enhanced" Interrogation Tactics Risk Criminal Prosecution – Landmark Report: Techniques Previously Authorized for CIA Use — Not Ruled Out by President's CIA Executive Order — Likely Violate U.S. Law |work=[[Physicians for Human Rights]] |date=August 2, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011084738/http://physiciansforhumanrights.org/library/news-2007-08-02.html |archivedate=October 11, 2007 }}
*[http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/us_law/etn/nomarks/exec-summary.asp "Leave No Marks: 'Enhanced' Interrogation Techniques and the Risk of Criminality"], A Report by Human Rights First and Physicians for Human Rights, July 2007
*[http://physiciansforhumanrights.org/torture/face-the-truth.html "President Bush and Congress must face the truth"] by Physicians for Human Rights, August 30, 2007</ref></blockquote>

The [[Constitution Project]] convened a review of interrogation and detention programs in the years after the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks. It concluded in 2013 that "it is indisputable that the United States engaged in the practice of torture" and that the nation's highest officials bore ultimate responsibility for it.<ref>{{Cite news |author= Shane, Scott |title= U.S. Practiced Torture After 9/11, Nonpartisan Review Concludes|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/16/world/us-practiced-torture-after-9-11-nonpartisan-review-concludes.html |quote= |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2013-04-16 |accessdate=2013-04-16 }}</ref>

==Ban on interrogation techniques==
On December 14, 2005, the [[Detainee Treatment Act]] was passed into law, setting the Army policy as standard for all agencies and prohibiting "cruel, inhuman, or degrading treatment or punishment."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2005/12/15/us-landmark-torture-ban-undercut |title=U.S.: Landmark Torture Ban Undercut |work=[[Human Rights Watch]] |date=December 15, 2005 |accessdate=July 24, 2018 }}</ref>

On February 13, 2008, the U.S. Senate, in a 51 to 45 vote, approved a bill clarifying this language, allowing only "those interrogation techniques explicitly authorized by the [[2006 Army Field Manual]]."<ref name="Senate Ban">{{cite web |url=https://www.jurist.org/news/2008/02/senate-backs-intelligence-bill/ |title=Senate backs intelligence bill restricting CIA interrogation tactics |first=Mike |last=Rosen-Molina |work=[[JURIST]] |date=February 13, 2008 |accessdate=August 5, 2018 }}</ref> ''The Washington Post'' stated:

<blockquote>The measure would effectively ban the use of simulated drowning, temperature extremes and other harsh tactics that the CIA used on [[al-Qaeda]] prisoners after the September 11, 2001, attacks.<ref name="WaPo Ban">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/02/13/AR2008021302888.html |title=Senate Passes Ban On Waterboarding, Other Techniques |first=Dan |last=Eggen |authorlink=Dan Eggen |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=February 14, 2008 |accessdate=August 5, 2018 }}</ref></blockquote>

President [[George W. Bush]] has said in a [[BBC]] interview he would veto such a bill<ref name="WaPo Ban"/><ref name="Veto">{{cite web |url=https://www.jurist.org/news/2008/02/bush-to-veto-intelligence-bill/ |title=Bush to veto intelligence bill restricting CIA interrogation tactics |first=Jaime |last=Jansen |work=[[JURIST]] |date=February 15, 2008 |accessdate=August 5, 2018 }}</ref> after previously signing an [[executive order (United States)|executive order]] that allows "enhanced interrogation techniques" and may exempt the CIA from [[Common Article 3 of the Geneva Conventions]].<ref name="Senate Ban"/>

On March 8, 2008, President Bush vetoed this bill.

<blockquote>Because the danger remains, we need to ensure our intelligence officials have all the tools they need to stop the terrorists", Bush said in his weekly radio address . "The bill Congress sent me would take away one of the most valuable tools in the war on terror&nbsp;– the CIA program to detain and question key terrorist leaders and operatives." Bush said that the methods used by the military are designed for interrogating "lawful combatants captured on the battlefield", not the "hardened terrorists" normally questioned by the CIA. "If we were to shut down this program and restrict the CIA to methods in the Field Manual, we could lose vital information from senior al Qaida terrorists, and that could cost American lives", Bush said.</blockquote>

[[Massachusetts]] senator [[Ted Kennedy|Edward Kennedy]] described Bush's veto as "one of the most shameful acts of his presidency". He said, "Unless Congress overrides the veto, it will go down in history as a flagrant insult to the rule of law and a serious stain on the good name of America in the eyes of the world."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/03/08/bush.torture.ap/index.html|title=Bush vetoes bill banning waterboarding|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/politicsNews/idUSN0736443620080308?sp=true|title=Bush vetoes bill outlawing CIA waterboarding|first=Reuters|last=Editorial|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/news/releases/2008/03/20080308.html |title=President's Radio Address |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311185628/http://www.whitehouse.gov/news/releases/2008/03/20080308.html |archivedate=March 11, 2008 |work=[[whitehouse.gov]] |date=March 8, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311020720/http://voanews.com/english/2008-03-08-voa10.cfm |archivedate=March 11, 2008 |url=http://voanews.com/english/2008-03-08-voa10.cfm |title=President Bush Vetoes Waterboarding Ban |accessdate=July 24, 2018 |first=Scott |last=Stearns }}</ref>

According to [[Jane Mayer]], during the transition period for then President-elect [[Barack Obama]], his legal, intelligence, and national-security advisers had met at the CIA's headquarters in [[Langley, Virginia|Langley]] to discuss "whether a ban on brutal interrogation practices would hurt their ability to gather intelligence", and among the consulted experts:

<blockquote>There was unanimity among Obama's expert advisers... that to change the practices would not in any material way affect the collection of intelligence.<ref name="Transition team">{{cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/the-new-yorker-blog/behind-the-executive-orders |title=Behind the Executive Orders |first=Jane |last=Mayer |authorlink=Jane Mayer |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=January 25, 2009 |accessdate=July 24, 2018 }}</ref></blockquote>

On January 22, 2009, President Obama signed [[Executive Order 13491]] requiring the CIA to use only the 19 interrogation methods outlined in the United States [[FM 2-22.3 Human Intelligence Collector Operations|Army Field Manual on interrogations]] "unless the Attorney General with appropriate consultation provides further guidance."<ref name="ObamaDirectives">Obama issues torture ban
*{{cite web |url=https://www.jurist.org/news/2009/01/obama-issues-torture-ban-orders-cia/ |title=Obama issues torture ban, orders CIA 'secret prisons' closed |first=Bernard |last=Hibbitts |work=[[JURIST]] |date=January 22, 2009 }}
*{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/first100days/2009/01/22/obama-issues-directives-detainees-interrogation-guantanamo/ |title=Obama Issues Directives on Detainees, Interrogation, Guantanamo |work=[[FoxNews]] |date=January 22, 2009 |accessdate=August 5, 2018 }}
*{{cite news |url=https://www.salon.com/2009/01/22/executiveorders/ |title=The Washington establishment's plans for Obama's executive orders |first=Glenn |last=Greenwald |authorlink=Glenn Greenwald |work=[[Salon.com]] |date=January 22, 2009 |accessdate=August 5, 2018 }}
*{{cite web |url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the_press_office/EnsuringLawfulInterrogations/ |title=Executive Order – Ensuring Lawful Interrogations |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126061153/http://www.whitehouse.gov/the_press_office/EnsuringLawfulInterrogations/ |archivedate=2009-01-26 |work=[[The White House]] |via=[[whitehouse.gov]] |date=January 20, 2009 |accessdate=August 5, 2018 }}</ref>

==Decision not to prosecute==
U.S. and international law states that if a country is unwilling or unable to prosecute its own officials for torture, an international tribunal may do so.<ref name = "Prosecution Abroad">{{Cite news |author=Somini Sengupta |title=Americans Involved in Torture Can Be Prosecuted Abroad |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/11/us/politics/americans-involved-in-torture-can-be-prosecuted-abroad-analysts-say.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 10, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-11 }}</ref>

The [[United Nations Special Rapporteur|United Nations' Special Rapporteur on Torture]], [[Human Rights Watch]], and American legal scholars have called for the prosecution of Bush administration officials who ordered torture, conspired to provide legal cover for torture, and CIA and DoD personnel and contract workers who carried it out.<ref name="CallsforProsection">Calls for Prosecution

*{{cite news |author=The Editorial Board, NYT |title=Prosecute Torturers and Their Bosses |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/22/opinion/prosecute-torturers-and-their-bosses.html |quote= |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 21, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-26 }}
*{{cite news |author=Kenneth Roth |title= The CIA torturers should be prosecuted |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/the-cia-torturers-should-be-prosecuted/2014/12/12/f034acae-8159-11e4-9f38-95a187e4c1f7_story.html |quote= |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date= December 12, 2014|accessdate=2014-12-13 }}
*{{cite web |url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/192809/prosecute-john-yoo-says-law-school-dean-erwin-chemerinsky |title=Prosecute John Yoo, Says Law School Dean Erwin Chemerinsky |last1=Wiener |first1=Jon |authorlink=Jon Wiener |date=2014-12-12 |website=[[The Nation]] |accessdate=2014-12-15}} 
*{{cite news |author= Rebecca Gordon|title=They should all be tried: George W. Bush, Dick Cheney and America's overlooked war crimes|url=http://www.salon.com/2016/04/30/they_deserved_to_be_tried_george_w_bush_dick_cheney_and_americas_overlooked_war_crime_partner/ |quote= |work=[[Salon (website)|''Salon'' (website)]] |date=April 30, 2016 |accessdate=2016-05-01 }}</ref> Former Bush administration attorney John Yoo has said that CIA officers risk prosecution for acts outside what the Justice Department specifically authorized.<ref name= "legal risk"/> A dozen lower-ranking Defense Department personnel were prosecuted for abuses at [[Abu Ghraib torture and prisoner abuse#Repercussions|Abu Ghraib]]; one CIA contractor who beat a prisoner to death in Afghanistan was prosecuted for assault.<ref name="MyUser_The_New_York_Times_April_20_2015c">The CIA contractor persists in denying that beating someone to death over the course of two days was torture. {{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/20/us/a-singular-conviction-amid-the-debate-on-torture-and-terrorism.html |title=A Singular Conviction Amid the Debate on Torture and Terrorism |newspaper=The New York Times |date= April 19, 2015 |author=Clyde Haberman |accessdate= April 20, 2015}}</ref>

However, neither US domestic nor international prosecution of high-ranking officials is likely.<ref>{{cite news |author=James Reini |title=Why Bush Won't be Prosecuted over CIA Torture |url = http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/12/why-bush-won-be-prosecuted-over-cia-torture-2014121161914372298.html |quote= |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=December 11, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-15 }}</ref>

===US domestic prosecution refused===
President Obama, while condemning torture, ruled out prosecuting his Bush administration predecessors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/barackobama/11291476/Why-wont-Barack-Obama-prosecute-CIA-torturers.html |title=Why won't Barack Obama prosecute CIA torturers? |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date= December 12, 2014 |author=Raf Sanchez |accessdate= June 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name=latimes2009-04-17>{{cite news |last1= Miller |first=Greg |last2=Meyer |first2=Josh |date=April 17, 2009 |title=Obama assures intelligence officials they won't be prosecuted over interrogations |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/apr/17/nation/na-interrogation17 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=July 10, 2016}}</ref> According to University of California Law School Dean [[Christopher Edley Jr.]], who served on President Obama's transition team, the decision not to prosecute predated Obama's taking office and was due to concern about a backlash by leaders of the military, the [[National Security Agency]] and the CIA.<ref>{{cite news |author=Bob Egelko |title=Obama ally says torture probe could have prompted CIA 'revolt' |url=http://blog.sfgate.com/nov05election/2011/09/10/obama-ally-says-torture-probe-could-have-prompted-cia-revolt/ |quote= |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=September 10, 2011 |accessdate=2015-01-05 }}</ref> In an interview, [[Ben Rhodes (White House staffer)|Ben Rhodes]], [[Deputy National Security Advisor (United States)|Deputy National Security Advisor]] under Obama, commented on the difficult political problems that torture prosecutions would have created, both in distracting from the administration's response to the [[Great Recession]] and potentially alienating the president from his own agencies.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The Intercept]] |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/06/22/is-it-time-to-reckon-with-obamas-foreign-policy-legacy/ |title=Confronting the Consequences of Obama's Foreign Policy |date=June 22, 2018 |accessdate=June 25, 2018 |first=Mehdi |last=Hasan |authorlink=Mehdi Hasan |quote=You know, he's sitting there, he's looking at over the abyss of the Great Depression and the disruption of taking on a prosecution of U.S. officials, sorting out who is in that bucket and who isn't, would have been a consuming thing for him to do and really something that could have broken apart essentially, you know, the connective tissue of the president to his own agencies.}}</ref> Legal analysts such as [[Eric Posner]] and [[Andrew Napolitano]] have said that prosecutions would create a precedent putting Obama administration officials at risk of politically motivated prosecutions by their successors.<ref name="ObamaSaysNoProsection">Commentary on why Obama won't prosecute
*{{Cite news |author=Eric Posner |title=Why Obama Won't Prosecute Torturers |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/view_from_chicago/2014/12/senate_torture_report_why_obama_won_t_prosecute_cia_and_bush_administration.html |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=December 9, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-11 }}
*{{Cite news |author=Judge Andrew Napolitano |title=Why Obama Won't Prosecute Crimes Laid Out in Senate's Torture Report|url=http://insider.foxnews.com/2014/12/10/why-obama-wont-prosecute-cia-crimes-laid-out-senate-torture-report |quote= |work=[[Fox News]] |date=December 10, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-11 }} 
*{{cite news |author=David Shribman |title=Presidents Don't Prosecute Their Predecessors |url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2009/05/03/look_to_the_future_not_the_past_96313.html |quote=[T]here have been 43 changes of presidents, and always this rule, never written but never broken, has prevailed: Presidents let their predecessors be judged by the merciless jury of history, not by the temporal verdicts of courts.|work=[[Real Clear Politics]] |date=May 3, 2009 |accessdate=2016-03-07 }}</ref>

The US Department of Justice announced that there will be no trials even of those who went well beyond what the [[Torture Memos]] allowed, including those who tortured detainees to death.<ref name="US Justice Department">US Justice Department says no prosecutions
*{{Cite news |author=Scott Shane |title=No Charges Filed on Harsh Tactics Used by the C.I.A. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/31/us/holder-rules-out-prosecutions-in-cia-interrogations.html |quote= |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 30, 2012 |accessdate=2014-12-11 }}
*{{Cite news |author=Glen Greenwald |authorlink=Glenn Greenwald |title= Obama's justice department grants final immunity to Bush's CIA torturers |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2012/aug/31/obama-justice-department-immunity-bush-cia-torturer |quote= |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=August 31, 2012 |accessdate=2014-12-11 }}</ref> The rationale has not been disclosed. In response to a [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|FOIA]] lawsuit, the Obama administration argued that the rationale should be kept secret because "disclosing them could affect the candor of law enforcement deliberations about whether to bring criminal charges."<ref name="DOJ FOIA">{{cite news |last=Savage |first=Charlie |authorlink=Charlie Savage |date=December 10, 2014 |title=U.S. Tells Court That Documents From Torture Investigation Should Remain Secret |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/11/us/politics/us-tells-court-that-documents-from-torture-investigation-should-remain-secret.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=December 16, 2014 }}</ref>

===Foreign prosecution possible but unlikely===
There is no [[Statute of limitations#International crimes|statute of limitations for war crimes]] in international law. However, prosecutions in either the [[International Criminal Court]], or in the courts of a particular nation invoking the doctrine of [[universal jurisdiction]], are also regarded as unlikely.<ref name = "International charges">{{Cite news |author=Philip Bump |title=Why Dick Cheney and the CIA don't need to worry about international criminal charges |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/12/10/why-dick-cheney-and-the-cia-dont-need-to-worry-about-international-criminal-charges/ |quote= |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 10, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-11 }}</ref>

The U.S. under the Bush administration "unsigned" the treaty that had conferred on the International Criminal Court [[jurisdiction]] over Americans.<ref name = "Renounced Treaty">{{Cite news |title=US renounces world court treaty |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/1970312.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |date=May 6, 2002 |accessdate=2014-12-11 }}</ref> In addition, President Bush signed the 2002 [[American Service-Members' Protection Act]] allowing military invasion of [[The Hague]] to rescue any Americans the court might detain for war crimes trials. Some torture occurred in CIA [[black site]] prisons in countries that remain parties to the treaty, like Poland, Afghanistan, Lithuania, and Romania. But for political reasons those countries are not in a position to initiate a prosecution, nor to extradite US officials to face charges.<ref name = "International charges"/>

Invoking the [[universal jurisdiction]] doctrine, the [[Center for Constitutional Rights]] tried first in Switzerland and then in Canada to prosecute former President George Bush, on behalf of four tortured detainees. Bush cancelled his trip to Switzerland after news of the planned prosecution came to light.<ref name = "Bush Switzerland">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2016-02-01 |title=George W. Bush cancels visit to Swiss charity gala over fears he could be arrested on torture charges |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1354211/George-W-Bush-cancels-Switzerland-visit-fears-arrest-torture-charges.html |newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |access-date=2016-04-12 }}</ref> Bush has traveled to Canada but the Canadian government shut down the prosecution in advance of his arrest.<ref name = "Center Prosecution">{{cite news |author1=Matt Eisenbrandt |author2=Katherine Gallagher |title=Halting Canadian Bush Prosecution Violated International Obligations|url=http://jurist.org/hotline/2012/01/eisenbrandt-gallagher-bush.php |work=[[Jurist]] | quote=Canada disregarded an opportunity to shatter the global impunity Bush enjoys and in so doing violated international law. |date=January 17, 2012  |accessdate=2016-03-06 }}</ref>  The Center has filed a grievance with the United Nations for Canada's failure to enforce the [[Convention Against Torture]], on which action is pending.<ref name = "Center Prosecution"/>

===Consequence of failing to prosecute===
Without any prosecutions the possibility remains that a future presidential administration could claim torture is legal and revive its practice.<ref name="Torturelaweviscerated">Torture becomes mere policy choice

*{{Cite news |author=Scott Lemieux |title=Torture Without Accountability|url=http://prospect.org/article/torture-without-accountability |quote= |work=[[The American Prospect]] |date=September 3, 2012 |accessdate=2014-12-11 }}
*{{Cite news |author=Anthony D. Romero |title=Pardon Bush and Those who Tortured |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/09/opinion/pardon-bush-and-those-who-tortured.html |quote= |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 8, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-11 }}
*{{cite news |author=Juliet Lapidos |title=Dick Cheney Makes a Great Case for Prosecuting Torturers | url=http://takingnote.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/12/15/dick-cheney-makes-a-great-case-for-prosecuting-torturers/ |quote= |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 15, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-15 }}
*{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2015/04/21/new_amnesty_report_criticizes_obama_handling_of_torture_evidence_could_america.html |title=New Amnesty Report criticizes Obama handling of torture evidence: Could America torture again? |newspaper=Slate.com |date=April 21, 2015  |author=Joshua Keating |accessdate= April 21, 2015}}</ref> 
In February 2016, several leading U.S. presidential candidates openly argued for reintroducing torture.<ref name = "Republicans Try To Outdo Each Other On Torture">{{Cite news |title=Republicans Try To Outdo Each Other On Torture |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/gop-debate-torture-waterboarding_us_56b6ae8ce4b04f9b57d9e72c |work=[[Huffington Post]] |date=February 6, 2016 |accessdate=2016-02-07 }}</ref> Including President [[Donald Trump]] who expressed his desire to bring back waterboarding.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-38753000 |title=Donald Trump says he believes waterboarding works |work=[[BBC]] |date=January 26, 2017 |accessdate=August 6, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2017/01/25/politics/donald-trump-waterboarding-torture/index.html |title=Trump on waterboarding: 'We have to fight fire with fire' |work=[[CNN]] |date=26 January 2017 |accessdate=August 5, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/01/26/waterboarding-absolutely-works-donald-trump-discusses-torture/ |title=Donald Trump: Torture 'absolutely works', says US President in interview with ABC News: Thursday morning briefing |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=26 January 2017 |accessdate=August 5, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/01/trump-torture/514463/ |title=Can Trump Bring Back Torture? |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=26 January 2017 |accessdate=August 5, 2018 |first=Adam |last=Serwer }}</ref> 
The U.S. reluctance to punish torturers has set back the fight against torture worldwide, according to [[Juan E. Méndez]], the United Nations' special rapporteur on torture.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Nick Cummin-Bruce |title= Torture Fight Set Back by U.S. Failure to Prosecute, U.N. Official Says |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/12/world/juan-mendez-calls-for-cia-torture-prosecutions.html |quote= |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 11, 2014 |accessdate=2014-12-11 }}
</ref>

==Prosecution of John Kiriakou==
Former CIA officer [[John Kiriakou]] in 2007 was the first official within the U.S. government to confirm the use of [[waterboarding]] of [[al-Qaeda]] prisoners as an interrogation technique, which he described as torture.<ref name=a>{{cite news |first=Joby |last=Warrick |author2=Dan Eggen |date=11 December 2007 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/12/10/AR2007121002091.html |title=Waterboarding Recounted |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=20 April 2009}}</ref><ref name="Dallas">{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Davis |date=12 December 2007 |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/opinion/viewpoints/stories/DN-markdavis_12edi.ART.State.Edition1.36db21e.html |title=His second guess is wrong |work=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |accessdate=20 April 2009}}</ref>

On October 22, 2012, Kiriakou pleaded guilty to disclosing [[classified information]] about a fellow CIA officer that connected the [[covert operative]] to a specific operation. He was sentenced to 30 months in prison on January 25, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-21610806 |title=Ex-CIA officer Kiriakou "made peace" with leak decision |work=[[BBC]] News |date=February 28, 2013}}</ref>

==European Court of Human Rights decisions==
On July 24, 2014, the [[European Court of Human Rights]] ruled that [[Poland]] violated the [[European Convention on Human Rights]] when it cooperated with the US, allowing the CIA to hold and torture [[Abu Zubaydah]] and [[Abd al-Rahim al-Nashiri]] on its territory in 2002–2003. The court ordered the Polish government to pay each of the men 100,000 euros in damages. It also awarded Abu Zubaydah 30,000 euros to cover his costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28460628|title=Poland 'helped in CIA rendition', European court rules|publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-court-rules-against-poland-in-cia-rendition-case-1406193988|title=European Court Assails Poland Over Role in CIA 'Black Sites'|author=Gabriele Steinhauser and Jess Bravin|date=July 25, 2014|work=Wall Street Journal}}</ref>

On 31 May 2018, the ECHR ruled that [[Romania]] and [[Lithuania]] also violated the rights of Abu Zubaydah and Abd al-Rahim al-Nashiri in 2003-2005 and in 2005-2006 respectively, and Lithuania and Romania were ordered to pay 100,000 euros in damages each to Abu Zubaydah and Abd al-Nashiri.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-44313905|title=Lithuania and Romania complicit in CIA torture - European court|date=May 31, 2018|work=BBC News}}</ref>

