==A==
{{glossary}}
{{term|1= Abacus |content= [[Abacus (architecture)|Abacus]] }}
{{defn|1= A flat slab forming the uppermost member or division of the capital of a column. }}

{{term|1= Accolade |content= [[Accolade (architecture)|Accolade]] }}
{{defn|1= A sculptural embellishment of an arch. }}

{{term|1=Aisle  |content= [[Aisle]] }}
{{defn|1=Subsidiary space alongside the body of a building, separated from it by columns, piers, or posts. }}

{{term|1=Ante-choir  |content= [[Ante-choir]] }}
{{defn|1=The space enclosed in a church between the outer gate or railing of the [[rood screen]] and the door of the screen.}}

{{term|1= Apron |content= [[Apron (architecture)|Apron]]  }}
{{defn|no=1 |1= raised panel below a window or wall monument or tablet.}}
{{defn|no=2 |1= open portion of a marine terminal immediately adjacent to a vessel berth, used in the direct transfer of cargo between the vessel and the terminal.}}
{{defn|no=3 |1= [[concrete]] slab immediately outside a vehicular door or passageway used to limit the wear on asphalt paving due to repetitive turning movements or heavy loads.}}

{{term|1= Apse |content= [[Apse]] }}
{{defn|1= Vaulted semicircular or polygonal end of a chancel or chapel.  That portion of a church, usually Christian, beyond the "crossing" and opposite the nave.  In some churches, the choir is seated in this space. }}

{{term|1= Araeosystyle |content= [[Araeosystyle]] }}
{{defn|1=An architectural term applied to a [[colonnade]], in which the [[intercolumniation]] is alternately wide and narrow.}}

{{term|1= Arcade |content= [[Arcade (architecture)|Arcade]] }}
{{defn|1= Passage or walkway covered over by a succession of [[arch]]es or [[Vault (architecture)|vault]]s supported by [[column]]s.  Blind arcade or arcading: the same applied to the wall surface.}}

{{term|1= Arch |content= [[Arch]] }}
{{defn|1=A curved structure capable of [[Span (architecture)|spanning]] a space while supporting significant weight. }}

{{term|1= Architrave |content= [[Architrave]] }}
{{defn|1=Formalized lintel, the lowest member of the classical entablature. Also the molded frame of a door or window (often borrowing the profile of a classical architrave). }}

{{term|1= Arris |content= [[Arris]] }}
{{defn|1=Sharp edge where two surfaces meet at an angle such as the corner of a square column or shaft. }}

{{term|1= Arrowslit |content= [[Arrowslit]] }}
{{defn|1= A thin vertical aperture in a fortification through which an archer can launch arrows. }}

{{term|1= Articulation |content= [[Articulation (architecture)|Articulation]] }}
{{defn|1=Articulation is the manner or method of jointing parts such that each part is clear and distinct in relation to the others, even though joined. }}

{{term|1= Ashlar |content= [[Ashlar]] }}
{{defn|1=Masonry of large blocks cut with even faces and square edges. }}

{{term|1= Atlas |content= [[Atlas (architecture)|Atlas]]}}
{{defn|1=A support sculpted in the form of a man, which may take the place of a column, a pier or a pilaster. }}

{{term|1= Atrium |content= [[Atrium (architecture)|Atrium]] }}
{{defn|1=(plural: atria) Inner court of a Roman or C20 house; in a multi-story building, a toplit covered court rising through all stories. }}

{{term|1= Attic |content= [[Attic]] }}
{{defn|1= Small top story within a roof above the uppermost ceiling. The story above the main [[entablature]] of a classical [[façade]].}}
{{glossary end}}

==B==
{{glossary}}
{{term|1= Bahut |content= [[Bahut (architecture)|Bahut]] }}
{{defn|1=A small parapet or attic wall bearing the weight of the roof of a cathedral or church. }}

{{term|1= Balconet |content= [[Balconet]] }}
{{defn|1=A false balcony, or railing at the outer plane of a window. }}

{{term|1= Ball flower |content= [[Ball flower]] }}
{{defn|1=An architectural ornament in the form of a ball inserted in the cup of a flower, which came into use in the latter part of the 13th, and was in great vogue in the early part of the 14th century. }}

[[File:Orna138-Docken-Baluster.png|right|thumb|A page of fanciful balusters]]
{{term|1= Baluster |content= [[Baluster]]}}
{{defn|1=A Small moulded shaft, square or circular, in stone or wood, sometimes metal, supporting the coping of a parapet or the handrail of a staircase; a series of balusters supporting a [[handrail]] or [[Coping (architecture)|coping]]. }}

{{term|1=Bar-stayed girder |content= [[Bar-stayed girder]]}}
{{defn|1=A structural member of inadequate capacity for its load or span that is augmented by one or two steel bars anchored to each bearing end at or above the centroid of the girder to assume the tension forces.  The bar(s) runs down and below the girder and stand off the girder on one or more struts anchored to the girder at its bottom surface.  The struts are sized to accept the compressive forces imposed without bending. The load limit to this member is the crippling capacity (horizontal failure) of the girder. }}

{{term|1=Bargeboard |content= [[Bargeboard]]}}
{{defn|1=A board fastened to the projecting gables of a roof.}}

{{term|1= Barrel vault |content= [[Barrel vault]] }}
{{defn|1=An architectural element formed by the extrusion of a single curve (or pair of curves, in the case of a pointed barrel vault) along a given distance. }}

{{term|1= Bartizan |content= [[Bartizan]] }}
{{defn|1=An overhanging, wall-mounted turret projecting from the walls, usually at the corners, of medieval fortifications or churches. }}

{{term|1= Basement |content= [[Basement]] }}
{{defn|1=Lowest, subordinate storey of building often either entirely or partially below ground level; the lowest part of classical elevation, below the [[piano nobile]]. }}

{{term|1= Basilica |content= [[Basilica]] }}
{{defn|1=Originally a Roman, large roofed hall erected for transacting business and disposing of legal matters.; later the term came to describe an aisled building with a clerestory. Medieval cathedral plans were a development of the basilica plan type. }}

{{term|1= Batement Lights |content= [[Batement Lights (architecture)]]}}
{{defn|1=The lights in the upper part of a perpendicular window, abated, or only half the width of those below.<ref>{{EB1911|inline=1|wstitle=Batement Lights|volume=3|page=509}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Batter |content= [[Batter (walls)]]}}
{{defn|1=Upwardly receding slope of a wall or column. }}

{{term|1= Battlement |content= [[Battlement]] }}
{{defn|1 =A parapet (i.e., a defensive low wall between chest-height and head-height), in which rectangular gaps or indentations occur at intervals to allow for the discharge of arrows or other missiles. }}

{{term|1= Bay |content= [[Bay (architecture)|Bay]]s }}
{{defn|1=Internal compartments of a building; each divided from the other by subtle means such as the boundaries implied by divisions marked in the side walls (columns, pilasters, etc.) or the ceiling (beams, etc.). Also external divisions of a building by fenestration (windows). }}

{{term|1=Bay window |content= [[Bay window]] }}
{{defn|1=Window of one or more storeys projecting from the face of a building. [[Canted window|Canted]]: with a straight front and angled sides. [[Bow window]]: curved. [[Oriel window|Oriel]]: rests on corbels or brackets and starts above ground level; also the bay window at the dais end of a medieval [[great hall]]. }}

{{term|1= Belfry |content= [[Bell tower|Belfry]] {{anchor|Belfry|Bell tower }}}}
{{defn|1=Chamber or stage in a tower where bells are hung. The term is also used to describe the manner in which bricks are laid in a wall so that they interlock. }}

{{term|1= Bench table |content= [[Bench table]] }}
{{defn|1=Stone seat which runs round the walls of large churches, and sometimes round the piers; it very generally is placed in the porches.}}

{{term|1= Bond |content= [[brickwork|Bond]] }}
{{defn|1=Brickwork with overlapping bricks. Types of bond include stretcher, English, header, Flemish, garden wall, herringbone, basket, American, and Chinese. }}

{{term|1= Boss |content= [[Boss (architecture)|Boss]] }}
{{defn|no=1|1=Roughly cut stone set in place for later carving.}}
{{defn|no=2|1=An ornamental projection, a carved [[Keystone (architecture)|keystone]] of a [[ribbed vault]] at the intersection of the [[ogive]]s. }}

{{term|1= Bossage |content= [[Bossage]] }}
{{defn|1=Uncut stone that is laid in place in a building, projecting outward from the building, to later be carved into decorative moldings, capitals, arms, etc. Bossages are also [[wiktionary:Rustic|rustic]] work, consisting of stones which seem to advance beyond the surface of the building, by reason of indentures, or channels left in the joinings; used chiefly in the corners of buildings, and called rustic [[Quoin (architecture)|quoin]]s. The cavity or indenture may be round, square, chamfered, beveled, diamond-shaped, or enclosed with a [[cavetto]] or [[listel]].<ref name=Cyclopaedia-1728>{{Cite Cyclopaedia 1728|title=Bossage|url=https://archive.org/stream/Cyclopediachambers-Volume1/cyclo1#page/n269/mode/2up/search/bossage|volume=1|page=269}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Boutant |content= [[Boutant]] }}
{{defn|1=Type of support. An [[arc-boutant]], or flying buttress, serves to sustain a vault, and is self-sustained by some strong wall or massive work. A pillar boutant is a large chain or jamb of stone, made to support a wall, terrace, or vault. The word is French, and comes from the verb ''bouter'', "to butt" or "abut".<ref>{{Cite Cyclopaedia 1728|title=Boutant|url=https://archive.org/stream/Cyclopediachambers-Volume1/cyclo1#page/n269/mode/2up/search/bossage|volume=1|page=269}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Bracket |content= [[Bracket (architecture)|Bracket]] (see also [[corbel]]) }}
{{defn|1=Weight-bearing member made of wood, stone, or metal that overhangs a wall. }}

{{term|1= Bressummer |content= [[Bressummer]] }}
{{defn|1=(literally "breast- beam") – Large, horizontal beam supporting the wall above, especially in a jettied building. }}

{{term|1= Brise soleil |content= [[Brise soleil]] }}
{{defn|1=Projecting fins or canopies which shade windows from direct sunlight. }}

{{term|1= Bullseye window |content= [[Oeil-de-Boeuf|Bullseye window]] }}
{{defn|1=Small oval window, set horizontally. }}

{{term|1= Bulwark |content= [[Bulwark]]}}
{{defn|1=[[Barricade]] of [[beam (structure)|beams]] and [[soil]] used in 15th- and 16th-century [[fortification]]s designed to mount [[artillery]]. On board [[ship]]s the term refers to the [[woodwork]] running round the ship above the level of the [[deck (ship)|deck]]. Figuratively it means anything serving as a defence. Dutch loanword; Bolwerk }}

{{term|1= Buttress |content= [[Buttress]] }}
{{defn|1=Vertical member projecting from a wall to stabilize it or to resist the lateral thrust of an arch, roof, or vault. A [[flying buttress]] transmits the thrust to a heavy abutment by means of an [[arch]] or half-arch. }}
{{glossary end}}

==C==
{{glossary}}
{{term|1= Cancellus |content= [[Cancellus]]}}
{{defn|1=(plural: Cancelli) Barriers which correspond to the modern balustrade or railing, especially the screen dividing the body of a church from the part occupied by the ministers hence chancel. The Romans employed cancelli to partition off portions of the courts of law.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Cancelli |volume=5}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Cantilever |content= [[Cantilever]] }}
{{defn|1=An unsupported overhang acting as a lever, like a flagpole sticking out of the side of a wall. }}

{{term|1= Capital |content= [[Capital (architecture)|Capital]] }}
{{defn|1= The topmost member of a column (or pilaster). }}

[[image:Porch of Maidens.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The Caryatid Porch of the [[Erechtheion]], [[Athens]], 421–407 BC]]
{{term|1= Caryatid |content=[[Caryatid]] }}
{{defn|1=A sculpted female figure serving as an architectural support taking the place of a column or a pillar supporting an entablature on her head.}}

{{term|1= Casement window |content= [[Casement window]] }}
{{defn|1=Window hung vertically, hinged one side, so that it swings inward or outward. }}

{{term|1= Cauliculus |content= Cauliculus, or caulicole {{anchor|cauliculus|caulicole}}}}
{{defn|1=Stalks (eight in number) with two leaves from which rise the helices or spiral scrolls of the [[Corinthian capital]] to support the [[abacus]].<ref>{{cite EB1911|wstitle=Cauliculus|short=1|volume=5|page=557}}</ref>}}

{{term|1= Cella |content= [[Cella]] }}
{{defn|1=The inner chamber of a temple in classical architecture. }}

{{term|1= Chalcidicum }}
{{defn|1=In Roman architecture, the vestibule or portico of a public building opening on to the forum, as in the basilica of Eumachia at Pompeii, and the basilica of Constantine at Rome, where it was placed at one end. See: Lacunar.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Chalcidicum|volume=5|page=804}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Chancel |content= [[Chancel]] (also Presbytery) {{anchor|chancel|presbytery}}}}
{{defn|1= In church architecture, the space around the altar at the east end of a traditional Christian church building, including the choir and sanctuary.}}

{{term|1= Chandrashala |content= [[Chandrashala]] }}
{{defn|1=The circular or horseshoe arch that decorates  many Indian cave temples and shrines. }}

{{term|1= Chimera |content= [[Chimera (architecture)|Chimera]] }}
{{defn|1=Chimera, as an architectural feature, means a fantastic, mythical or grotesque figure used for decorative purposes. }}

{{term|1= Chimney |content= [[Chimney]] }}
{{defn|1=A structure which provides ventilation. }}

{{term|1= Chresmographion}}
{{defn|1=Chamber between the pronaos and the [[cella]] in Greek temples where oracles were delivered.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Chresmographion|volume=6|page=273}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Cincture }}
{{defn|1=Ring, list, or [[Annulet (architecture)|fillet]] at the top and bottom of a column, which divides the shaft from the capital and base.<ref>{{Cite Cyclopaedia 1728|title=Cincture|url=https://archive.org/stream/Cyclopediachambers-Volume1/cyclo1#page/n371/mode/2up/search/cincture|volume=1|page=371}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Cinque cento |content= [[Cinque cento]] }}
{{defn|1=Style which became prevalent in Italy in the century following 1500, now usually called 16th-century work. It was the result of the revival of classic architecture known as Renaissance, but the change had commenced already a century earlier, in the works of [[Lorenzo Ghiberti|Ghiberti]] and [[Donatello]] in sculpture, and of [[Filippo Brunelleschi|Brunelleschi]] and [[Leone Battista Alberti|Alberti]] in architecture.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Cinque Cento|volume=6|page=377}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Cippus |content= Cippus }}
{{defn|1=(plural: cippi) A low, round or rectangular pedestal set up by the Romans for military purposes such as a milestone or a boundary post. The inscriptions on some cippi in the British Museum show that they were occasionally used as funeral memorials.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Cippus|volume=6|page=379}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Circulation |content= [[Circulation (architecture)|Circulation]] }}
{{defn|1=Describes the flow of people throughout a building. }}

{{term|1= Cleithral }}
{{defn|1=Term applied to a covered Greek temple, in contradistinction to [[hypaethral]], which designates one that is uncovered; the roof of a cleithral temple completely covers it.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Cleithral|volume=6|page=481}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Clerestory|content= [[Clerestory]] }}
{{defn|1=Upper part of the nave of a large church, containing a series of windows.}}

{{term|1= Coffer |content= [[Coffer]] }}
{{defn|1=A [[coffer]], in architecture, is a sunken panel in the shape of a square, rectangle, or octagon that serves as a decorative device, usually in a ceiling or vault. Also called caissons, or lacunar.{{sfn|Ching|1995|p=30}} }}

{{term|1= Colarin |content= Colarin or [[Hypotrachelium]]}}
{{defn|1=(also colarino, collarino, or hypotrachelium) The little frieze of the capital of the Tuscan and Doric column placed between the astragal, and the annulets. It was called [[hypotrachelium]] by [[Vitruvius]]. }}

{{term|1= Column |content= [[Column]] }}
{{defn|1= A structural element that transmits, through compression, the weight of the structure above to other structural elements below. }}

{{term|1= Compluvium |content= [[Compluvium]] }}
{{defn|1=Latin term for the open space left in the roof of the [[atrium (architecture)|atrium]] of a Roman house ([[domus]]) for lighting it and the rooms round.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Compluvium|volume=6|page=811}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Coping |content= [[Coping (architecture)|Coping]] }}
{{defn|1= The capping or covering of a wall.}}

{{term|1= Corbel |content= [[Corbel]] }}
{{defn|1=A structural piece of stone, wood or metal jutting from a wall to carry a superincumbent weight. }}

{{term|1= Corinthian order |content= [[Corinthian order]] }}
{{defn|1=One of the three [[Classical order|orders]] or organisational systems of Ancient Greek or classical architecture characterised by columns which stood on the flat pavement of a temple with a base, their vertical shafts fluted with parallel concave grooves topped by a [[Capital (architecture)|capital]] decorated with [[Acanthus (ornament)|acanthus]] leaves, that flared from the column to meet an [[Abacus (architecture)|abacus]] with concave sides at the intersection with the horizontal beam that they carried. }}

{{term|1= Cornice |content= [[Cornice]] }}
{{defn|1=Upper section of an entablature, a projecting shelf along the top of a wall often supported by brackets or [[corbel]]s. }}

{{term|1= Cresting |content= [[Cresting (architecture)|Cresting]] }}
{{defn|1= Ornamentation along the ridge of a roof.}}

{{term|1= Cross Springer }}
{{defn|1=Block from which the diagonal ribs of a vault spring or start.  The top of the springer is known as the skewback.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1||volume=7|page=510|wstitle=Cross Springer}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Crypt |content= [[Crypt]] }}
{{defn|1=stone chamber beneath the floor of a church or other building. It typically contains [[coffin]]s, [[Sarcophagus|sarcophagi]], or [[Relic|religious relics]]. }}

{{term|1= Crypto-porticus |content= [[Crypto-porticus]] }}
{{defn|1=Concealed or covered passage, generally underground, though lighted and ventilated from the open air. One of the best-known examples is the crypto-porticus under the palaces of the Caesars in Rome. In Hadrians villa in Rome they formed the principal private intercommunication between the several buildings.<ref>{{Cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Crypto-porticus|volume=7|page=566}}</ref> }}

{{term|1=Cuneus}}
{{defn|1=A wedge-shaped division of the Roman theatre separated by the ''scalae'' or stairways.<ref>Vitruvius v. 4.</ref> This shape also occurred in medieval architecture.}}

{{term|1= Cupola |content= [[Cupola]] }}
{{defn|1=A small, most often dome-like, structure on top of a building. }} 

{{term|1=Cyrto-style}}
{{defn|1=A circular projecting portico with columns.<ref>{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Cyrto-style|page=706|volume=7|short=x}}</ref>}}
{{glossary end}}

==D==
{{glossary}}
{{term|1= Diastyle }}
{{defn|1=Term used to designate an [[intercolumniation]] of three or four diameters.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Diastyle}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Diaulos |content= [[Diaulos (architecture)|Diaulos]] }}
{{defn|1=[[#Peristyle|Peristyle]] round the great court of the [[palaestra]], described by [[Vitruvius]], which measured two stadia (1,200&nbsp;ft.) in length, on the south side this peristyle had two rows of columns, so that in stormy weather the rain might not be driven into the inner part. The word was also used in ancient Greece for a foot race of twice the usual length.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Diaulos}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Diazoma }}
{{defn|1=A horizontal aisle in an ancient [[Greek theater]] that separates the lower and upper tiers of  semi-circular seating and intersects with the vertical aisles.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Diazomata}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Dikka |content= [[Dikka]] }}
{{defn|1=Islamic architectural term for the tribune raised upon columns, from which the Koran is recited and the prayers intoned by the Imam of the mosque.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Dikka}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Dipteral }}
{{defn|1=Temples which have a double range of columns in the [[#Peristyle|peristyle]], as in the temple of [[Diana (mythology)|Diana]] at [[Ephesus]].<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Dipteral}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Distyle |content= [[Distyle in antis]] }}
{{defn|1=Having two columns }}

{{term|1= Distyle-in-antis |content=  }}
{{defn|1=An architectural term for a portico having two columns between two [[anta (architecture)|anta]]<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Distyle}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Dodecastyle }}
{{defn|1=Temple where the [[portico]] has twelve columns in front, as in the portico added to the [[Temple of Demeter]] at [[Eleusis]], designed by [[Philo]], the architect of the arsenal at the [[Peiraeus]].<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Dodecastyle}}</ref> }}

[[File:Classical orders from the Encyclopedie.png|right|thumb]]
{{term|1= Doric order |content= [[Doric order]] }}
{{defn|1=One of the three [[Classical order|orders]] or organisational systems of Ancient Greek or classical architecture characterised by columns which stood on the flat pavement of a temple without a base, their vertical shafts fluted with parallel concave grooves topped by a smooth [[Capital (architecture)|capital]] that flared from the column to meet a square [[Abacus (architecture)|abacus]] at the intersection with the horizontal beam that they carried. }}

{{term|1= Dormer |content= [[Dormer]] }}
{{defn|1=A structural element of a building that protrudes from the plane of a sloping [[roof]] surface. Dormers are used, either in original construction or as later additions, to create usable space in the roof of a building by adding headroom and usually also by enabling addition of windows. }}

{{term|1= Dosseret |content= Dosseret, or [[impost block]] {{anchor|Dosseret|impost block}}}}
{{defn|1=Cubical block of stone above the capitals in a Byzantine church, used to carry the arches and vault, the springing of which had a superficial area greatly in excess of the column which carried them.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Dosseret}}</ref> }}

{{anchor|Double-depth plan}}{{term|1= Double-depth plan}}
{{defn|1=A plan for a structure that is two rooms deep but lacking a central corridor.<ref>{{cite web|title=Double depth plan|url=http://thesaurus.historicengland.org.uk/thesaurus_term.asp?thes_no=546&term_no=137705|website=English Heritage Online Thesaurus|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref>}}

{{term|1= Dromos }}
{{defn|1=Entrance passage or avenue leading to a building, tomb or passageway. Those leading to [[beehive tomb]]s are enclosed between stone walls and sometimes in-filled between successive uses of the tomb.{{sfn|Deurer|2011}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Glossary of terms related to the catacoombs |publisher=International catacomb society |url=http://www.catacombsociety.org/glossary.html }}</ref> In ancient Egypt the dromos was a straight, paved avenue flanked by sphinxes.{{sfn|Deurer|2011}}<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1|wstitle=Dromos}}</ref> }}
{{glossary end}}

==E==
{{glossary}}
{{term|1= |content= [[Entablature]] }}
{{defn|1=A superstructure of moldings and bands which lie horizontally above columns, resting on their capitals. }}

{{term|1= |content= [[Entasis]] }}
{{defn|1=The application of a convex curve to a surface for aesthetic purposes. Its best-known use is in certain orders of Classical columns that curve slightly as their diameter is decreased from the bottom upward. It also may serve an engineering function regarding strength. }}

{{term|1= Ephebeum }}
{{defn|1=Large hall in the ancient [[Palaestra]] furnished with seats, the length of which should be a third larger than the width. It served for the exercises of youths of from sixteen to eighteen years of age.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Ephebeum |volume=9 |page=669}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Epinaos }}
{{defn|1=Open [[vestibule (architecture)|vestibule]] behind the [[nave]]. The term is not found in any classic author, but is a modern coinage, originating in Germany, to differentiate the feature from the [[opisthodomos]], which in the [[Parthenon]] was an enclosed chamber.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Epinaos}}</ref> }}

{{term|1=Estrade}}
{{defn|1=French term for a raised platform or [[dais]]. In the [[Levant]], the estrade of a divan is called a Sopha, from which comes our word 'sofa'.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Estrade |volume=9 |page=800 }}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Eustyle }}
{{defn|1=[[intercolumniation]] defined by [[Vitruvius]] as being of the best proportion, i.e. two and a quarter diameters.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Eustyle |volume=9 |page=957}}</ref> }}
{{glossary end}}

==F==
{{glossary}}
{{term|1= Facade |content= [[Facade]] }}
{{defn|1=An exterior side of a building, usually the front.}}

{{term|1= Fanlight |content= [[Fanlight]] }}
{{defn|1=Window, semicircular or semi-elliptical in shape, with glazing bars or tracery sets radiating out like an open fan. }}
{{term|1= fascia |content= [[Fascia (architecture)|Fascia]] }}
{{defn|1=Horizontal board attached to the lower end of rafters at the eaves. }}
{{term|1= Feretory }}
{{defn|1=Enclosure or chapel within which the ferreter shrine, or tomb (as in Henry VII.'s chapel), was placed.<ref>{{cite EB1911|short=1 |wstitle=Feretory}}</ref> }}

{{term|1= Flushwork |content= [[Flushwork]] }}
{{defn|1=The decorative combination on the same flat plane of [[flint]] and [[ashlar]] stone.  It is characteristic of medieval buildings, most of the survivors churches, in several areas of Southern England, but especially [[East Anglia]]. If the stone projects from a flat flint wall, the term is '''proudwork''' – as the stone stands "proud" rather than being "flush" with the wall. }}

{{term|1= Flying buttress |content= [[Flying buttress]] }}
{{defn|1=A specific type of [[buttress]] usually found on a religious building such as a cathedral. }}

{{term|1= Flying rib }}
{{defn|1=An exposed structural beam over the uppermost part of a building which is not otherwise connected to the building at its highest point. A feature of H frame constructed concrete buildings and some modern skyscrapers. }}

{{term|1= Footprint }}
