{{term|1= Hip roof |content= [[Hip roof]] }}
{{defn|1=A type of roof where all sides slope downwards from the ridge to the eaves. }}

{{term|1= Hyphen }}
{{defn|1=Possibly from an older term "heifunon"<ref name="name">{{cite web |url= http://en.allexperts.com/q/Architecture-2369/heifunon.htm |title= Q & A about "heifunon." |author= Richard Taylor, [[American Institute of Architects|AIA]] |work= All Experts, owned by [[About.com]] |date= 10 April 2007 |quote= '''[[Question]]''':  In the film ''[[At First Sight (1999 film)|At First Sight]]'' the word "heifunon" was mentioned as a supposed architectural term…  Is there really such a word? I can find nothing with that spelling.  '''Answer''':  My guess is that they're talking about a "hyphen" … a connecting piece between two larger masses of a building.  It is most commonly used when referring to [[American colonial architecture|Colonial-era houses]] - especially the [[Colonial Georgian|Georgian style]].  Take a look at the photo <nowiki>[</nowiki>of the [[James Brice]] house<nowiki>]</nowiki> at [http://www.bsos.umd.edu/anth/aia/james_brice_house.htm the top of this page.]  The hyphens are clearly visible on either side of the main house block.  The masses connected to the main house by the hyphens are called dependencies. |deadurl= yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081012052215/http://en.allexperts.com/q/Architecture-2369/heifunon.htm |archivedate= 12 October 2008 |df=  }}</ref> – a structural section connecting the main portion of a building with its projecting "dependencies" or wings. }}
{{glossary end}}

